name: Pallium
description: Start in the cave on the deepest jugs; move through good ledges and walk the feet across; transfer feet with some core tension and hooks to obtain a good but crumbly hold to exit the cave and get onto the face; with hands on the ledge, find your feet and make a mantle to top out. Refer to photos for route idea. A nice cleaning brush will help with loose debris/sand/soil. Standout movements and a fantastic finish.

name: Another Mother
description: Start just down and left from the Cowabunga Direct start with a couple small/low holds.  Move right into the Cowabunga Direct pocket and continue up/left without using any other holds from Cowabunga Direct to gain a stance or to the tip and drop.This is a fairly old line at the park as used to be done on TR and climbing to the top, much better boulder problem though.

name: Asinine Behavior
description: Start just left of Intergalactic Quaalude Trip on a high right diagonal good hold and reach out left for a less than ideal hold.  Climb up and slight left and go into the left part of the obvious seam and drop.

name: Astral Projection
description: Same as the rope climb but with pads.  Start right of Rocket Man on a large positive hold, move up to a large edge and then a big move up and left into another large ledge and drop.

name: Astral Traverse
description: A traverse that starts/ends on Rocket Man and Inappropriate Behavior.  Climb up about 8' and work your way through the large ledge used on Astral Traverse.  There is an eliminate that takes the large ledge off called Minus One Traverse that goes around V5.

name: Ballerina
description: Start to the right and under the main bulge of the park, just left of Doug's Roof.  This is the Ballerina bulge and holds some of the best problmes at the park.  Start low on right edge and left on the sidepull.  Climb straight up, move over left into the book and finish with a top out.  Ballerina High starts after the crux of the low problem and is much easier.

name: Ballerina High
description: Stack pads, use stump, or jump start to a two hand rail, pull through the open book, walk over to chips and climb down. Could be a bad fall on the retaining wall be careful. A dirty and wet direct start begins awkwardly a bit lower on a two handed undercling/sidepull, and goes at V5

name: Ballerina Left
description: Eliminate - Start same as Ballerina High and eliminate everything on the right side of the book and top out.

name: Ballerina Right
description: Another eliminate on the Ballerina Bulge but it's a decent one.  Same start as Ballerina, and as the name suggests you only use the holds on the right of the open book and holds beneath.  The corner is on as the steepness lacks other holds, but the ledge for Ballerina proper and everything above is definitely off.

name: Blind Faith
description: Same start as Walk on By.  After the first couple of moves, go up into a crimp and out onto the arete finishing in the crescent moon.  The Walk on By jug is off as the problem climbs the arete straight up.

name: Bonsai
description: Same start as Ride or Die (the iron plate) and get into the pocket and good edge up and left.  Left hand up to the softball sloper and then move onto the face finishing same as More Power Scotty.

name: Buns Dyno
description: On the left side of the Buns Bulge on the huge ledges the obvious start.  Paste the feet somewhere underneath and jump for the top.  Going out left to the lower ledge or using any other starting holds other than the ledge itself is not part of the problem, although they're still fun.

name: Buns Machine Gun
description: Eliminate - Start on the left of the Buns Bulge low below the obvious ledge bisecting the bulge.  Start hold has hands stacked below eliminated ledge climbing on the lower set of holds into a deep/good pocket then top out same as Buns Machine Gun High.A rock broke sometime in 2020 creating another good hold on the line making it somewhat softer than the V5 assigned but it's still a good problem with a solid top out.

name: Buns Machine Gun Full Value
description: Start as far back left on the bulge as you can with two slopey edges.  Throw up a heel and climb into Buns Machine Gun proper.  Instead of toping out after the large pocket stay low and continue right into the large triangle shaped pocket.  Move up staying off all the good edges used on Buns Machine Gun toping out on the arete.

name: Buns Machine Gun High
description: Start at the left of the large crack in the Buns Bulge.  Climb right and when the crack ends top it out.

name: By Crackie
description: Start 4' left of Saving Grace and a little lower in a large undercling pocket.  Climb straight up topping out on the Saving Grace Bulge.

name: Climb or die
description: Same as ride or die just in reverse

name: Cold Turkey
description: Start down in the corner with an awkward start and trend right.  Good little boulder problem topping out on the Ballerina Bulge. Rock quality is not good above Ballerina. As such, it is not recommended climbing higher.

name: Comedy Of Terrors
description: Start at the side pull and crimp just below Ballerina (green tick marks shows start) Use slippery feet under you and crank up and right (red ticks shows holds). Crux is just over the lip, holding on to a sloper and throwing for a small crimp.

name: Comedy of Terrors Direct
description: Start on the left facing block as for Ballerina Direct and make a big move out right, continue trending up and left into the chossy headwall. Top out and downclimb Ballerina until you can drop off.

name: Cowabunga Direct
description: Start on the iron plate, same as Ride or Die.  Climb up and slightly left into good holds under the small roof and then through thin edges up to the obvious ledge or into the large seem.

name: D-Bag
description: Start left hand in seam and right hand under the roof on an edge.  Climb along the lip of the small roof finishing up on the arete gaining a stance on the face, same as Blind Faith.

name: Delightful midgets
description: Same as midget’s delight just in reverse

name: Despondecy Direct
description: Difficult beginning with a few condensed moves. Get ready for either a dyno or a lengthly lock off to a decent hold in the middle of the route. Find hands on a small crimp, get high feet and pull hard on a crimpy sidepull to finish the rest of the route. Last ten feet are 5.easy

name: Despondecy Direct Natural
description: Low crux boulder problem using non-manufactured holds. The big starter slot, the smaller pocket/slot up left and the chiseled hold above the crescent edge are off.Drop off at the jug after the crimps, or continue up past another crux to easier climbing above.

name: Despondency
description: Same start as Despondency Direct, but traverse right and up a series of right-facing sidepulls to bypass the big move to the jug. Once you get to jug, the finish is the same as DD.

name: Despondency Dyno
description: Start on the high slots and go for the good ledge.

name: Diagonal Crack
description: Start same as Grady.  Climb through the large diagonal crack above the Grady line and top out in the middle of the bulge right of Grady.

name: Diving board
description: Same as the mantle but on the right side instead

name: Enigma
description: Start with a right hand side-pull on the right side of the arete at chest height and your left on a side-pull in some carbonate deposit hold. Step your left foot anywhere you can get a clean foot and match your right heel to your right hand and go.  The problem ends at the very large side-pull.

name: Finesse
description: A direct route through the horizontal rail of Three Mules and heading straight to the top.Boulder problem just goes into the horizontal rail for a nice little warm up.

name: Grady
description: Sit start on the right side of the bulge about 15’ left of the diving board/mantle problem. There is a fist sized crack about 3’ in length below chest level that serves as the start. Eliminate the large diagonal crack near the start and everything above the obvious ledge system traversing it across to the left and topping it out when it peters out.

name: Grady Low
description: Same as Grady but eliminate the high ledge system, staying on the lower holds, topping out same as Grady.

name: Heart and Soul Direct
description: Best Dyno at the park.  Left hand on a decent sidepull and right on an edge, paste your feet and go out right to a big slash.  Match and call it good, gain the face or top out into dirt.

name: Highball aka Pocket Problem
description: Large pockets, easy boulder. Great warm up.

name: Hollywood
description: Start high on the carbinite jug on Walk on By, climb up and right along the lip of the roof into a big jug.  Go straight up from the gaining a stance on the jug and jump down.  this can obviously be linked to the end of V4 Walk on By for a full value pump.

name: Inappropriate Behavior
description: Start on the slab and reach your way up through some easy technical climbing until you get to the arete where the 5.12 crux is to some small edges after a high step.  There is two ways to pull the crux, without the arete  make a reachy move to an edge using a toe hook.

name: Insomnia
description: Same start as Enigma and get into the left side pull and cross over into the slash on Heart and Soul, then up into the finishing large pocket.

name: Intergalactic Quaalude Trip
description: Start on the high block left of Finesse.  Climb straight up through a sloping edge for the left and into a large seam where the boulder problem end.  Continue straight to the top on TR to finish the route.Typical Grand Ledge 10b.

name: Intimidator Direct
description: Start on two small stacked two edges left and below the Intimidator Block on the lip.  High left heel on the larger step or right heel on a small/good edge and climb into the traditional start for the route and gain a stance.  Contrived but its alright.

name: Little Crusher Direct
description: Hand to foot and up the slab. Requires adult assist or the pre-pubescent amygdala of Alex Honnold.

name: Living on the Ledge
description: Start on the two obvious crimps and smear up the slab. Nice topout and an easy exit on the backside.

name: Low Rider
description: Start on the Intimidator block and climb right through edges finishing on Cowabunga Direct.

name: Mantle Problem Variation, The
description: Eliminate - Same start as the Mantle Problem, eliminate all holds on the sides of the roof and go straight out instead of finishing up and left.

name: The Mantle Problem
description: Sit start and climb up and pull the left side of the small roof.  Top out and walk around on the stairs.

name: Mass Hysteria
description: Tricky intro into Comedy of Terrors Direct. Start with hands in the jug part of a decent left facing vertical slash and traverse left until you can gain the good crimp under the roof below the Comedy of Terrors Direct headwall.

name: Max Scene Arete
description: Start on the low block and move into a thin edge with the right hand.  Work out left staying on the face and finishing in the large triangle feature or top out a few more feet of easier climbing.

name: MHL (Mass Hysteria Lite)
description: Start same as Mass Hysteria traversing left.  Instead of moving up into A Comedy of Terrors Direct, continue traversing into Ballerina and top out.This is reversing the Suicide Machine line that Jamie Emerson established in 2000 or so.  Locals looked at this for years afterwards with no success.  When Brendan Baars came along he not only finally did the long-standing project reversing the traverse, he added the hardest line to top it out creating Mass Hysteria which is an amazing line...some of us just ain't that strong!

name: Midget’s delight
description: This is an older problem and has changed over the years because of erosion and how much lower the ground is now on the west side of the great roof.Start/finish on the Walk on By starter block and the right most set of holds on the wall before the corner to the Mermaid Wall.

name: Mini Crack
description: Sit start in short vertical crack on right side of the wall.  Straight up and top out for a nice warm up.

name: More Power Scotty
description: Start same as Ride or Die (the iron plate) and move up the face into the obvious seam and drop.  The large ledge out right is off.

name: The No-hands Slab
description: Great little slab to practice balance on. The intended way to climb it is without using elbows, arms, or knees to aid you in climbing this slabby rock. Great fun to try out just for kicks. It unfortunately doesn't help warm up your hands for other climbing.

name: Pigeon Shit Direct
description: Start on the ground just left of the rock pedestal that Pigeon Shit starts on.  Left hand in small pocket and right in sidepull crack and make your way up and slightly left into jug and the rope route.

name: The Pretzel
description: Make a long move from a slightly awkward undercling to a pocket then continue up on crimps to the top. The starting feet are often greasy, but this little route has some interesting movement.This is an old sandbagged Grand Ledge problem that can be bouldered out.  Start with opposing hand on block at head height (in red).  Move into good pocket follow by a good two-finger pocket and on up.  There is an easier variation (in blue) starting right of this and meeting with the main line.  Both finish in the good triangle shape hold up high.

name: Professor P AKA Scofic Scam
description: Start on a decent left facing side-pull and crank with the right to a hold just over the mini roof. Find a foot and launch to the jug up and left. Top out.

name: Rathke's Revenge
description: Start right hand in the pocket and left hand on a pinch/edge in the roof and shoot up and left into the hueco then top out.

name: Rathke's Roof
description: Start as Up Yours Direct:  Start low with feet on bare rock surrounded by moss. Continue straight up the left side of the dihedral face, tending more left than straight up. The roof has some absolutely blind reaches to two finger pockets.  This climb might be extremely reach dependent.

name: Reflections
description: Start left of the arete and just left of the "9" carved into the rock above.  Climb up through crimps into seem and up into the "9" finishing on the ledge or topping out rather high off the deck.

name: Resistance
description: Start left of Ludwig's Dude on small pockets.  Move up and right into the slash, left into the side and finish on the ledge.  Top rope to finish to the top.  Jamie Emerson first finished this is in 2000 and it stood as the hardest problem in the park until recently with Dylan Bark's V10 D-Bag.

name: Ride or die
description: Start low and to the right of Cowabunga sit start. Traverse left staying low till you end on the start hold of Intimidator

name: Rocket Power
description: Start on Rocket Man and traverse right around the corner, across Despondency and onto the pillar in the corner.  Traversing either way is about the same difficulty but offers a different sets of moves.

name: Saving Grave
description: Start left of the “SAVING GRACE 8/5/27”   engraving on the overhanging slopey bulge.  Start on the jug 4’ left and below the engraving and climb up into the   faint water groove avoiding the huge ledges to the rightStart left of the “SAVING GRACE 8/5/27” engraving on the overhanging slopey bulge. Start on the jug 4’ left and below the engraving and climb up into the faint water groove avoiding the huge ledges to the right.

name: Scofic Scam Right Project
description: Start same as Scofic, move left hand up, right onto a bad edge, left up onto a bad sloper and shoot for a good hold.  I don't think this has ever been done and is still a project at the park.

name: Second Thought
description: Start of Doug. Reach shelf and either continue up or if bouldering just down climb or come down chips

name: Slag Traverse
description: Long black streak of rock, climber's left of "Saving Grace." Standard traverse is left to right.

name: Suicide Machine
description: Start same as Ballerina and traverse right through some very funky moves.  Finish matched on the good rail just left of Up Yours Direct start.

name: Thailand
description: Start a couple feet left of Max Scene Arete on good lower block.  Climb up the arete eliminating all the large holds out left leaving you a couple small edges and a useful knob.  End in the triangle hold and drop.

name: Tooth Right
description: Just like it sounds, sit start on the right of the tooth and climb the short arete with a nice top out.

name: The Tooth
description: Sit start with both hands as low as you can go with your left heel hooked and placed in a slight depression. Continue up the arete and top out at the end. A great little warm up.

name: Top Tier Dyno
description: Start a few feet left of Mini Crack, grab an edge at chest level and shoot for the top block slightly left.

name: The Treat
description: Start just below of The Trick on a low and obvious block.  Climb the face without using the large crack sticking to the arete and some edges.There is a large and intimidating looking rock behind this climb but it doesn't really come into play.  The lower part of the climb falls come straight down and as you get higher the tendency is to drift left and the rock is not really close to the drop zone.

name: Trick Arete Project
description: Start on low obvious block and climb the arete only.  There's the jug low and a small micro edge about 3/4 of the way up the arete.  Finish on the large ledge system same as Trick and Treat.

name: The Trick Direct
description: Same start as the Trick, eliminate the arete and climb straight up using a small edge high and right.

name: The Trick Dyno
description: Get into the a set of holds around 6' up and launch for the top.

name: The Trick
description: Start on the face with both hands at chest height, then get the half moon shaped hold. Eventually, get on the right arete and fire to the obvious finishing ledge and drop off.This can be topped out or top roped to the top but it is not recommended it is loose and dirty and not as fun as the lower section.

name: Under the Rainbow
description: Sit start on the rock in front of the sun and up through the the large crack

name: unknown E
description: Sit start on low holds under the black overlap. Stay right of the rounded arête, climb to the jugs or contend with the filthy top out for bonus points.

name: Up Yours Direct
description: Start left of Doug's Roof on low jug and left sidepull.  Climb straight up heading for the slot at the top of the face, up and left of the "Up Yours" mono and end there.  Kind of a high fall from the top but the landing is good.

name: Up Yours Super Direct Project
description: Start same as Up Yours Direct move out and left to the high arete and up.  The holds get really thin after the first couple moves getting matched into a crescent shaped hold midway up.

name: V1 Exit stage left
description: Climb the arete and exit stage left.

name: Viper
description: Move along pockets and decent feet until you're under the V and can reach up to top out (see picture). I call this a V1 compared to other problems around here but if you don't have the reach for the first big move or don't have nice edges on your shoes for the very last move then this will be more tough. If there is a previously established name for this, please leave a comment and I'll edit the name.

name: Walk on By
description: Start on the obvious shelf under the roof at the left side of the great roof.  Climb staight out and then left gaining a stance on the face.  Call it good or TR to the top with 5.9 climbing, much better broulder problem than TR.

name: Wall Street
description: Start between the mermaid carving and rock pedestal in the corner on a good ledge.  Climb up on thin edges, use the mermaid with a right hand and get into the obvious pockets and up.  There is a good ledge below the top, call it good here ad drop or go for the dirty top out.

name: WG Cundy
description: Start just down from Thailand and just before Saving Grace.  Grab a small pocket and the arete with the right and work up through the carving the climb derives its name.

name: WG Cundy Eliminate
description: Sit start on low block left of the proper route.  Traverse right through thin edges, eliminate the large feature out right, and go straight up to gain a stance.

name: Wheeties
description: Start left of Enigma on 2 not so good edges.  Climb straight up into a worse set of crimps and finally into the crux set of crimps.  Exiting left to the good pocket is V5 but this is the old/original problem that's been around for a long time.

name: Wheeties Left
description: Same start as Wheeties except move left into the good pocket on the orange streak and then up.  Solid problem, super bad angled landing makes it rarely climbed.

name: Yellow Wall Dyno
description: Start on good edges at the six foot level and go all the way up the the large ledge about 12' up.  Going to the lower ledge is called the Jaundice Jump.

name: Yellow Wall Traverse
description: Start on either end of the wall traversing and staying below the 6' mark or so.  Good warm up area and usually the driest spot in the park.

name: Yellow Wall Traverse High
description: Start on either side of the wall traversing to the other end using the high line of jugs.

name: Boulder Wall
description: A simple traversing boulder wall. Plastic holds on plywood.

name: Big Holds, Huh? Alright, Welp, See Ya Later
description: A small roof to get around

name: Choss-o-rama
description: Very chossy RH side of small open book just north of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

name: I Saw God
description: Left corner arete

name: I'm Not good At Juggy Stuff
description: Lots of crimpers and some side pulls. Nice vertical face. very little choss. Lots of fossils in the rock. Crux is the mantle.

name: On the 8th Day He Created Choss
description: Very chossy LH side of small open book just north of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

name: The Secret Is In The Choss
description: Just South of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

name: Speed Is Safty
description: Just South of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

name: Attack of the Killer Bees
description: Good crack up to small roof.  Deceptively few holds coming over.  Cracks can be difficult to protect due to flare.

name: Batteries Not Included
description: Two pitch route, or make it one. Fun little cruiser climb.

name: Bolete
description: Two hand start on the bottom horizontal crack at the nose of this boulder. Utilize the top horizontal crack and the chossy looking growth on the right to straddle and climb straight up the nose. Some nice big moves get you to an easy mantle up top. Walk off to the left of this route.

name: Brookside Crack
description: Lowball boulder. Start on the crack and crimp to the left. Move up through the crack and top out.

name: Brown Eyed Woman
description: An easy out for Killer Bees up a small crack on the left side of the face.  Good first lead.

name: Bubblewrap Grips
description: Sit start on two crimps and work the compression feature on bubble wrap holds. Top out, and then top out again. Great rock quality and clean. Given a generic name because I'm sure it has been climbed before.

name: Dandruff
description: On the face directly below the large, woodpecker ridden red pine.  Large flakes and a good crack.  Very juggy, good for beginners.

name: dead collector
description: Sit start under the small roof using shallow pocket to start. Move in and left through good crimps. Pull the roof to the shallow edge, don't use lose sharp left lip. Traverse right on obvious edge to top on the right ridge.   Flat landing with one sharp rock.

name: Dog Bowl
description: Two hand start on the middle point of the bottom horizontal crack. Move straight up utilizing the above horizontal crack, slant cracks, and nice sloped lip up to a mantle top out. There's a big dish at the top you can use to help mantle but be warned, it collects water in wetter conditions. Walk off on the left side of the climb.

name: Free To Roam Tower
description: A large tower/buttress coming out of the wall just to the northeast of the ice falls area.  Good protection every 10-15 feet, variety of gear sizes needed.  Top rope access extremely difficult/impossible.  Excellent learner piece for first time leaders.  Can top out by traversing the top of the tower back to the wall and climbing the sides of a very steep, scree filled gully.  Climb the gully walls, not the gully itself, as it is NOT STABLE and has FATAL FALL potential.

name: God Jam'it
description: Climb up the left side of the block and gain the horizontal right-left tending crack. Move right all the way to the end and exit onto the face above.

name: Ice Fall
description: Slab climbing Keweenaw style! No real crux. Fun warm up climb.    *Ice climbing in the past on Ice Fall (go figure) when the conditions are right.

name: J.C. Superstar
description: Nice face climb perched above the forests of da U.P. eh! Cracks and ledges help your way. Variations on this one.

name: Last Call For Alcohol
description: Start up a flat featureless slab for the first 20 ft.  Hug the right side arete, as that's where most of your initial protection can be found.  Pull over a small roof/shelf and work your way left to two obvious large crescent shaped cracks.  Balancy to the top.

name: Lie Detector
description: Begin on the leaning slab and in the crack. Crux is pulling the roof. Finish 10-15 ft. after the roof.

name: Lip Traverse
description: Sit start and traverse the lip. Lowball.

name: Mossy Overhang
description: Squat start on sloping crimp rail with terrible feet. Pull through to holds trending toward prow. Top out on moss covered holds (needs a good scrub). Given a generic problem name because I'm sure it has been climbed before. Obvious line with hard opening moves. It's even hard to establish on the start hold. Stand start is about V4.

name: Obsession
description: Start from the ledge (15' above the ground) at the bottom of the lower slab. Head up right or left. Head past the small overhang and then the big one. Piton (if still remaining) was placed in 1981.

name: Obsession Direct
description: Head left from the lower ledge and up the arret and over the headwall. One bolt after the headwall?

name: Off the Scale
description: Tough overhanging face. Watch the pendulum and lead fall potential.

name: Patina Crimp Pinch
description: Start right hand on patina crimp pinch. Left hand on slopey horizontal or in crack. Move left through good edges. Has potential for a lower start, but is scrunchy. Given a generic name because I'm sure it has been done before.

name: Porcupine
description: Two hand start on the left side of the bottom horizontal crack. Move up and to the left utilizing the top crack and sharp slopers covered in iron inclusions (they can rip up your finger pads. Great grip!) to a mantle top out. Walk off on the left side of the climb.

name: Prow
description: This one is fun, but the ending is kind of lame because you can exit on the slab. There is a potential dyno just left of this Arete. The top would need some scrubbing. Given a generic name beause im sure it has been climbed before.

name: Rated P.G.
description: Crux: Gaining the arete and running bolts 1 and 2. This is a sporty fun climb with nice U.P. exposure.   Lead fall decker potential if your belayer is not fully engaged.

name: Rope-burn
description: The start is slanted and getting on this climb can prove interesting. The crux pretty much the whole climb. Climb the underclung flake/crack system up and tending left then finishing on slopers up and right. Rope-burn is a great boulder problem-ish climb which needs a TR, or 9-plus crash pads.    Be aware of the run of your rope on TR.*

name: Shit Hooks
description: Off-width to the right of Obsession. Head through the roof.

name: Stupid Human Tricks
description: This route starts straight up from below the headwall of Exotermic through the triangular roof.  It is the farthest to the left on this face.  The next route to the left is around the corner on Obsession face and that route name is Clavin's project.

name: Three Roofs
description: Straight up the dirty slab to the first roof, pull to the easy slab above.  Angle left up this slab to the left corner under the orange second roof.  Reach out and ascend the bomber flake up to the mantle.  A "thank god" ledge gives you time to sort out the small nuts needed to protect the crux (with bomber placements at your heals) which is the move out right around the 3rd roof.  Get established on the slab above and cruise to the treeded ledge.  At this point you need to choose where to stop.  This is the natural end to the climb and a bomber white pine anchor, but one rope will not get you down, and the pull from the tree is really tough and barely doable  (will be replacing webbing and rap rings.)  Or, you can continue up  the buttress on an easy featured slab and anchor on the white pine about 40' higher.  The rope will pull much easier from this tree.  There is no 4th class approach from either side of the buttress to toprope this route or walk down.  Sometimes has Perrigrine falcons nearby, so avoid if nesting perigrines are giving you the flyby.

name: Tobacco Road
description: The rating varies from 5.4 to 5.9 (left to right) on this face of cracks. Left of J.C. Superstar. Great setting for Cliff Dr. Lower from the belay tree and make the climb two pitches.

name: Yooper Trooper
description: Start as low as possible sitting on the inner boulder with hands on right rail and feet hooked on left rail. Compress and climb right rail till you can span the boulder.  Continue to the point of the prow, and rock over the top with solid right heel.

name: Alley Slab
description: Sit start with right hand jug and left hand crimp. Climb up using good crimps and topout.

name: Backyard BBQ
description: SDS with left hand side pull and right hand low rail. Pull up to side rail before reaching large jugs and an easy top out. Crux is the first move.

name: Cul de Sac Kid
description: Crouch start with left hand on arete and right hand on low rail. Climb up using the arete, then transition into Backyard BBQ to top out. Crux is transitioning from arete to holds on Backyard BBQ.

name: Dyno Egg
description: Sit start using right hand crimp and left hand on arete. Match on right start hold, and then bump right hand further right to another crimp. Dyno to the lip. Could be different beta using the arete.

name: Eddy's Edge
description: Compression start with left hand on large sloper, right hand on low sidepull. Move up to rail before bumping onto higher holds and moving for a heel hook. From here work left to sideways crimp before finding better footing and bumping up to good rail and mantling for the top out.

name: Horse’s Mane
description: Stand start matched on low block. Make a lieback transition into the higher blocks and climb up the arete to better holds up top. Crux is transitioning from low block.

name: Meteor-left
description: Start standing with left hand on small crimp and right hand in small mouth features (may only fit a few fingers). Bump hands to good rail before shifting weight and reaching left to flat knob feature (use intermediates as needed). Transition right to the quarzite strip of jugs halfway up the boulder before moving up into the crater feature and follow the easy top out on the left side of the crater. This 20+ foot climb is a lot of fun with good movement and neat features.

name: Meteoright
description: Stand start with compression using  left hand on a solid sidepull jug and right hand high on a crimp. Gain high feet and throw for a small crimp. Then climb up into a quartzite band to solid jugs. From here, traverse left and climb into the crater feature. Top out as if on Meteor-left. Crux is the beginning move throwing from compression to the high crimp.

name: Neighborhood Slab
description: Stand start on two side pulls. Climb up using slippery feet a prominent side pull/rail. Crux is reaching the jug just above the prominent side pull.

name: Painted Black
description: Stand start on good crimps and heel. Make a few bumps up into prominent jugs, then traverse left along a juggy crack/rail. Match on jug on far left of the overhanging boulder.

name: Potato Salad
description: Start low with left hand on a slanted rail and right hand on a lower rail. Climb up using the arete and good holds.

name: Rhino Horn
description: SDS on detached block using high jug with right hand and low side pull jug with left. Climb up along the crack using an obvious Rhino horn looking jug. Tricky top out for the grade.

name: Rhino Traverse
description: Start on low, large rightmost jug. Traverse left using solid rails and side pulls. Climb up Rhino Horn to finish. Crux is at the beginning.

name: Salmon Run
description: Start with right hand on large jug, left hand on side crimp. Climb up using jugs on arete and left hand crimps before gaining feet on large ledge. Easy top out

name: Scooby Snack
description: Stand start matching on prominent jug. Traverse left using good holds and topout using solid rails. Fun movement to warm up on.

name: Warm Up 1
description: SDS on two low jugs. Pull to standing and reach for good central jug before moving feet up and topping out. Like climbing a ladder.

name: White Belt
description: Stand start matched on a large jug. Climb up and topout using good holds.

name: Working the corner
description: Start matched on slopey jug. Make move up and left to a solid jug. Then throw a heel on the slopey jug and make some bumps up good holds and topout. Crux is topping out. Fun little problem with some pumpy/powerful moves. (Low juggy foot at the start is off, as it is pretty loose)

name: 1. Trapeze Artist
description: A proud sun-soaked route with quality stone and quality pro.

name: 10. Funnel Cake Frenzy
description: Similar start to route #9 but follows the crack. Finish at the anchors of route #9 by moving around the boulder at the top, can be a tricky last move!

name: 11. Ringmaster
description: The start can be difficult if you want it to be by starting in the corner underneath the large shelf. There is a staircase used to access the right most routes that you could use to start if avoiding the crux is desired. Otherwise, a very fun full body mantle onto a shelf is the crux before the first bolt. Climb left of anchors for easier terrain, in line for moderate, and a bit to the right for some harder to reach crimps/pockets. Anchors are placed for an easy top rope setup.

name: 12. Funambulism
description: Just on top of the staircase, route starts with big holds which continue most of the way up. Veer left or right slightly for some variation in difficulty and end at the placed anchors basically standing at the edge of the camping platform. Walk left to top out if desired (this can save you from using the walking path to get to the top).

name: 14. Snake Charmer
description: Climb up the ‘staircase’ to get to the start, first 2 bolts are a gimme, crux is at the 4th bolt during a series of crack moves. One more big move to stick the anchors.

name: 15. Amputee
description: Climb up the ‘staircase’ to get to the start. Similar style to the route on its left, but smaller holds all around and no crack to help. Smear, smear, smear, good luck if it’s wet.

name: 2.  Oh No He Didn't?
description: Oh yes I DID!  Welcome to the wide world of offwidth/squeeze chimney climbing, except its protected by a few bolt's. Route starts out at 12" and maintains that for the first half then flares to 18".  There’s a thin seam running straight up one wall just inside this beast.  Quintessential chock stone rest mid route.

name: 3.  Ladies and Gentalmen
description: A fun Trad or Top Rope line just to the right of the off-width, ending in anchors for protection.  Staircase landings make it a great first time trad learner and there is plenty oh holds to hang onto.

name: 4.  Cotton Candy Buzz
description: Start just left of Bearded Lady in the corner. Ride the arete on the left side till the anchors.

name: 5.  The Bearded Lady
description: Slabby climb with some good opportunity for underclings and hand jambs. More difficult variations depending on which side of bolt line you climb. Finish just higher than the peak to your left at anchors. Crux at the start and roughly 3/4 of the way up.

name: 6. Cirque du Slabbay
description: Slabby climb with some good opportunity for underclings. More difficult variations depending on which side of bolt line you climb. Finish at anchors just higher than The Bearded Lady (the route to climbers' left). Crux at the start and roughly 3/4 of the way up.

name: 7. Bang!
description: Furthest left on the large slab wall, start on a scramble/slab and clip the first bolt. The second bolt protects a small ‘roof’ cruise to the top keeping just right of the arete/crack.

name: 8. Pow!
description: Middle route on the large slab, similar start as the route to the left, the ‘roof’ may be tricky for new climbers!

name: 9. Boom!
description: Furthest right, bolted route on the large slab, follow a crack that cuts to the left for the first 3 bolts, then some near vertical climbing for the finish. Crux is near the last bolt.

name: Black Luster Soldier
description: Sit start on far left side and traverse out right and then up obvious in-cuts at tallest portion of boulder.

name: Black Vertigo
description: Stand start matched on prominent ledge. Climb up aesthetic black streak trending right. Holds become less prominent near the top.

name: Blue Eyes Ultimate Dragon
description: Bail out of Dragon Master Knight with the use of Jar of Greed to top out just left of the start.

name: BPPV
description: Climb up slabby ladder system of jugs and great feet left of black streak. Easy climb, but good warm up for the rest of the problems next to it.

name: Cedar Crack
description: From a stand, climb up using the crack and prominent holds on the face, then top out.

name: Cedar Staircase
description: Sit start on good ledges for climb filled with great holds. The top has a close tree to be aware of when topping out.

name: Cedar Stretch
description: Start standing with side pull for the right hand and crimp for the left hand. Make a big move for the large ledge and work your way up using good hand holds to get the feet onto the ledge for an easy topout. Big move favors climbers with reach.

name: Cedar Warmup
description: Sit start with left hand on low jug and right hand on low rail. Climb up using solid jugs and top out.

name: Central Signs
description: Short route with a balancy/reachy finish.

name: Cochlea
description: Stand start on good hold at the base of the zig-zag crack. Climb up tall slab following the crack system. Fun movement with good holds throughout.

name: Cryptomite
description: From a stand, climb up the face trending left and top out. Beta felt a bit cryptic.

name: Crystal Wizard
description: Start matched on good side pull. Climb the tall face and to a somewhat committing top out.

name: Death Spar
description: Stand start with hands on right edge features and make few simple moves onto mega jug right before top-out. Beware of 'death spar' below.

name: Dragon Master Knight
description: Stand start with feet and hands out right. Travers left and finish on Black Luster Soldier. V4/5 with the wrong beta or for shorter people. V3 with the proper beta and a normal height. Avoid Jar of Greed (Jug near the start).

name: Dragon Scale
description: Stand start matched on good sidepull. Climb right utilizing flakey feature, then climb vertically utilizing arete and good holds along the face and topout.

name: Dwarves Dismay
description: SDS matched on crimpy rail. Climb up face trending right, and make a dynamic move to a prominent jug. Juggy holds make for an easing topout.

name: Epley Maneuver
description: Start directly right of Black Vertigo on diagonal crack system. Climb up the rock using the crack and good slabby features.

name: Fox Ear
description: Sit start on two crimps at the center of the boulder (same start as Fox Tail). Climb overhanging face trending right and top out. Fun problem with somewhat burly moves.

name: Fox Tail
description: Sit start on two good crimps. Climb the overhanging route using holds along the face and left arete. Fun climb with a somewhat committing top out.

name: Gimli Finds Another Way
description: Very fun V2. Start matched in a SDS on a low juggy rail. Climb up using lie-back/side pulls, before moving diagonally left to an obvious left hand jug in the middle of the wall. Easy top out.

name: Gnome Assassin
description: Stand out right and head left and up. Crux is a high reach just past midway through the route.

name: Gnome's Salvation
description: Travers the boulder to the right and finish up Gnome assassin.

name: Halfling's Staircase
description: Like the name implies, use the many juggy pocket features to climb up this rock for an easy top out.

name: Iron Treachery
description: Stand start matched on solid jug. Climb up tall face trending right and topout.

name: Little Arete
description: Stand start with right hand arete and left hand sloper on the face. Climb up using the arete and small holds along the face. Top out using good jugs.

name: Low Amperage
description: Sit start on good jugs. Climb up the face through interesting and balancy moves and top out.

name: Low Voltage
description: Sit start on low rail and move straight up with prominent features to comfortable topout.

name: Over Under
description: Stand start with hands matched on pocket sort of ledge. Find your way to the giant jug out right and work your way up for an easy slab finish.

name: Poplar Mantle
description: Stand start with right hand side pull and left palm on a solid jug. Climb up the face then mantle/top out.

name: Poplar Slab
description: Sit start matched on a good rail. Climb up some fun balancy moves and top out

name: Reddy to Roll
description: Stand start on jugs and follow prominent features for an easy topout. Landing is a slope that leads down a large hill.

name: Second Level Slab
description: Start with slopey hands to make 1-2 moves onto good features to topout

name: Sunset Slab
description: Stand start on a good rail. Climb the face and top out on good holds.

name: Up From Under
description: Stand start matched on high side pull. Make your way up the face using good holds along the face and top out. Fun movement.

name: Vertical Nystagmus
description: Start on easy rail system right of Epley Maneuver. Climb up the highest part of the boulder. Gain higher feet and follow a series crimps, small rails, and little cracks to move up the rock and top out.

name: Wolf Pup
description: Sit start with right hand crimp and left hand on a large rail. Climb up overhanging face trending left utilizing side pulls and decent features along left arete. Top out at the apex. Good climb with sustained difficulty throughout.

name: Arrowhead Arete
description: SDS with right hand on arete and left hand on prominent jug. Climb up the arete through good holds and top out. Crux is getting over the lip on the top out, as it is slightly overhanging.

name: Arrowhead Direct
description: Climb from two central jugs up to top of boulder. Arete is off til top out.

name: Funky Roof Project
description: Start on two sloping edges in the back of the roof. Work some foot magic to gain the lip before taking the brutal release and riding slick quartzite slopers to the mantle. All detached blocks are off!

name: Half Hearted
description: Crouch start matched on low juggy hold. Climb up using the arete and good holds along the face. Fun movement with crux at the top.

name: One Trick Pony
description: SDS with a sloper on the left arête and a low in-cut. Pull off the ground and make a few powerful bumps before compressing the prow and getting your hands on those glorious horns at the top.

name: Orange Peel
description: SDS with left hand low crimp and right hand jug. Climb up the low overhang and top out. Crux is getting over the lip when topping out.

name: Gateway to Granite Bluff
description: Stand start. Make your way up using good features to finish on jug at the top.

name: Wooded Chalice
description: Stand start matched on large jug/ledge. Climb the tall face using great holds and top out. Great movement with a crux being within the initial moves.

name: Boy Scout
description: SDS with left hand low crimp and prominent right hand side pull. Climb up using a jug and diagonal rail, then top out. Crux is at the start.

name: Eagle Scout
description: Unnecessary, but fun and balancey traverse. Start with left hand on low rail, right hand on sidepull. Pull to standing and use variety of underclings and sidepulls to make your way left working your feet on the prominent rail. Finish this problem by going up Girl Scout.

name: Fire Starter Arete
description: Stand start matched on right side of the boulder. Traverse left using great holds and top out into boy scout.

name: Girl Scout
description: Short, but somewhat fun problem. Start on diagonal mouth feature. Move up to slopey rail and pinch before finding jugs to top out on.

name: Hover
description: SDS with left hand low crimp, right hand on juggy arete, and heel hook on lower arete. Bump up the arete then utilize a pinch and small crimp above the arete. Gain higher feet and mantle. Crux is the mantle as holds get better up top.

name: Kraft
description: Burley but otherwise easy route. Starts on the same start as Hover, stay low traversing left and topping out on the far left side of the boulder.

name: Legacy Direct
description: Sit start with left hand crimp along prominent rail and left hand crimp below overhanging feature. Bump up and match on rail, then crossover to a small crimp. Throw for huge jug on the right side of the boulder. Gain a better foot using prominent rail and  then top out up and over the overhanging feature.

name: Merit Badge
description: SDS with hands matched on low rail. Work your way up using the arete for an easy top out.

name: Plato
description: Cleaned by David McCole. Wonderful route with 2 or 3 ways up the slippery rose quarts. All beta is fun and good. Route trends up and right to finish on some jugs.

name: Playground
description: Start with left hand crimp, right hand lower sidepull. Pull to higher left pinch before gaining higher feet and finding right hand crimp. Top out using variety of crimps, jugs and sidepulls. Good feet throughout.

name: Playtime
description: Start with left hand sidepull, right hand undercling. Work your way up using a series of good rails, jugs, and crimps. Plenty of holds to play around with to make this climb your own.

name: Ptolemy
description: Stand start on right hand crimp and left thumb on sidepull. Climb up trending left then topout using great jugs over the lip.

name: Socrates
description: Vary burly V4. Starting on obvious rail and pulling to obvious holds out Left to finish directly above start.

name: Gem
description: Follow Large crack from arrow to star on picture. Access top from the left

name: Blood Diamond
description: Blood Diamond is about 6ft to the left of Poly-Ticks and about 8ft to the left of Abba. About 10ft up you should see an obvious diamond shaped rock jutting about 4 inches out from the wall around it. Climb up to it, move very slightly to the left past a small roof through good holds to a small dyno and finish on decent holds.

name: Poly-Ticks
description: Poly-Ticks is a great sporty line that starts about 6ft to the left of Stop and have a picnic and goes up the white rock through a small roof then up the headwall to the top.

name: Stop and Have a Picnic
description: Stop and have a picnic is the obvious trad line that is on the far right side of Picnic Area Left. Follow a great selection of hand jams, stems and laybacks up a great line.

name: Diagonal Dish
description: This is a diagonal crack leaning to the right.  The climb is broken mid way by a ledge and has a large pin tree to climbers right on the top.

name: I Lost My Sole in the UP
description: On the right part of the wall, start left of a rock rib. Go up 2 moves to a short leftward traverse to a convenient tree stance. Next up to the ledge, move left to a shallow blocky groove. Top out on a large ledge. You can rappel from a huge pine tree 30 feet to the left. Gear is there but not very obvious. This is a pure gear route. FA was done in proper style, ground-up, on-site.

name: Double Crack
description: A crack climb that follows two parallel vertical cracks.  The difficulty increases near the top.

name: O Dub
description: This route is the squeeze chimney/ off width on the west side of the O'C Electric block.

name: O'C  Electric
description: Fun straight forward climb,lots of fun hand jamming the crack. Loose rocks removed on 1st assent, seems pretty clean. New at rating climbs so let me know what you think!

name: Rain Maker
description: A fun crack climb located in the large chimney.  It is possible use the crack and the chimney at the same time. It's quite easy to get nice rests by putting your back against the other chimney wall while climbing the crack.

name: The Deadpoint
description: Deadpoint off jugs and mantle the top

name: Finger Crack
description: The name says it all

name: The Seam
description: Follow face hold and a lieback

name: Sugar Loaf
description: On the southeast side of island.  Chossy.

name: Three Little Birds
description: Easy slab-like boulder problem in a fun setting.  Lots of good holds, but some are sharp.  Great view from the top.  (Other climbs possible on this big boulder)

name: 1.  'Tis Merely A Flesh Wound.
description: Dirty, body width, flaring crack immediately left of left most bolted line(Greg's Sonic Boom).  Doesn't see much traffic.  Takes good gear, but did I mention dirty.  Do the crag a favor and get on it to keep it clean.

name: 10. Protein Boy
description: Thin positive incut crimps down low lead to jug haul higher up. Good varied climbing. May be challenging onsight without the chalk highway to lead the way.

name: 11. Finger Lick'n Good
description: Thin steeper start leads to thinner crimps with some technical balance higher up.

name: 12. Flight Of The Gumbies
description: Follow a nice juggy start on a slightly overhanging wall to the small roof crux at the top of the route. Two ways to finish. Watch out your rope dosen't end up in the pond when you pull the rope.

name: 2. Greg's Sonic Boom
description: Furthest left bolted line.  Great textured slab.  Thank god ledge just below anchors.

name: 3. Gooble Gooble
description: Start at the base of Greg's Sonic Boom but head immediately right and up.  Stay mostly straight up line, wandering just a little.  Equipped by L.P. and P.P.

name: 4. Politely Insistent
description: Delicate slab.  Trust your feet, cuz your hands ain't great.  Equipped by L.P. and P.P.

name: 6. Fine Wine
description: First route right of talus. This is a great climb with an arsenal of fun moves and interesting holds. This climb really goes well after some "Cheese and Crackers".

name: 7. Cheese And Crackers
description: Follow the low angle slab with a large broken crack on the right. The crux of this climb is at the start. This climb really is nice and easy like cheese and crackers. Goes trad as well. Equipped by P.P.

name: 8. Carbo Boy
description: This is the classic local test piece.  The route is slightly overhanging with positive holds but a sustained cryptic longish crux. This climb can be real pumpy due to its overhanging nature and is a great workout.  An area must do!

name: 1.  Improbability Drive
description: Farthest route right on main wall.  Multiple boulder problems.  Time to get creative with this one.

name: 3.  Falling Zebras
description: Start on rock platform.  Consistently hard and a bit awkward.  Clipping the chains can be exciting.

name: 5.  Potty Mouth
description: Starts at the lowest point of the crag and follows the ridge/slab to anchors up past Zebras anchors.

name: 12  Midway Ramp
description: Begin by the tree and follow the diagonal ledge up to the big hanging flake. Continue up the right side of the flake. Watch for swings on top rope.

name: 13. Classic Crack
description: Begin in a shallow corner, negotiate a bulge to a ledge then finish up a thin crack. The bulge is the crux, but topping out can be sketchy. The route is leadable on Trad gear. Variations exist on the left and right sides of the upper crack.

name: 18. Five Overhangs
description: One of the best routes at Marquette Mountain. Can be easily top roped but also makes a nice trad lead. The crux is pulling the first lip and the gear is tricky. Be careful and have fun.

name: 19  Cam Café
description: Meander up the slab to the short hand crack in an upper block.

name: 21 Spider & the Fly
description: Slither up the slab crack then either jam the crack under the overhang (Spider) or reach far right across the gap to a good edge (Fly).

name: 22  Phil's Right Side Roof
description: Go up the slab to the roof. Pull the roof directly. A small hold on the left edge of the Roof is useful.

name: 8  Overhang Notch
description: Begin to the right and follow an easy ramp up to the "Notch" then straight up.

name: Dark Necessities
description: Start crouched beneath the lower of the two cracks. Climb up to a crux double finger lock beneath the lip. Heady with excellent movement.

name: Double Cracks
description: Start as for Lost in the Choss. Traverse left into Dark Necessities. Cool rock, nice holds, but a less than inspiring sequence.

name: Lost in the Choss
description: SDS matched on a left facing arête feature. Climb up (don't go left to the ramp) to a one move crux just beneath the top out. A bit contrived.

name: Pale Blue
description: Start crouched with a left hand sidepull and right on the arête. Neat grips and a fun compression sequence takes you to the top out.

name: The Gales of November
description: SDS with left hand on a blocky side-pull feature on the left arête and right on a small edge. A nice mixture of face and compression climbing leads up the gently overhanging prow.   The ramp on the left side of the boulder is off, this makes the start slightly awkward, but gives more value to the remainder of the climb.

name: Bath Bomb
description: SDS with both hands on the blocky rail feature. Make a powerful move to the right arête and compress it to the top. Harder for short folks.

name: Bathtub
description: SDS with a left hand crimp at the lip of the bulge and right hand on the blocky fin feature. Surmount the bulge and head through nice edges on the slab before topping out.

name: Body Wash
description: SDS with right hand in a left facing slot and left hand on a small crimp. Climb the left face of the dihedral. Topping out straight up (without traversing left into the crack) sustains the route's difficulty and provides for a more full-value climb.

name: Bubbles
description: SDS matched on the seam low on the arête. A techy mantle leads to a few small holds beneath a mellow top out.

name: Conditioner Crack
description: SDS matched on a crimp seam. Awkward climbing in the dihedral leads to a sweet crack and mellow top out.

name: Loofah Roofah Left
description: SDS with a low pinch on the flake for the right and a sloping crimp for the left. Climb up and into the neat roof feature. Trend left and top out.   A super hard variation may be possible starting matched on the slopey crimps directly under the roof.

name: Loofah Roofah Right
description: SDS with right hand on a low side-pull and left on an edge. Traverse left to the big flake before working into the cool roof feature. Skirt left to top out. Fun moves on cool holds.

name: Power Shower
description: SDS with left hand in the slot and right on a nearby sloper. Head right towards a micro crimper before powering through the overhanging bulge. Brutal.

name: Rubber Ducky
description: Start crouched with left hand in a slot and right on a side-pull around the arête. A few awkward moves lead to a mellow top out.

name: Shampoo
description: Start as for Loofah Roofah Right, but head straight up through the bulging arête and top out.

name: Sudzy
description: SDS with left hand on a sharp crimp and right in a tips slot. An improbable mantel and a few tenuous slab moves lead to the top out. A very satisfying climb.

name: Towel Whip
description: SDS with left hand on a side pull in the dihedral and right far out on an edge. A perplexing move gains you the crack which leads to the top out.

name: The Water Heater
description: SDS from the rock matched on a side pull. Fun climbing on nice ledges leads to a thoughtful top out.

name: Fuzzy Peach
description: This route is the most right of the dihedral systems.  Climb up a chimney like feature to a flake and continue to a nice ledge

name: Banana Splitter
description: Start low and climb the right angling splitter crack.

name: Flapjacked
description: Start matched in a huge undercling. Ride small edges beneath the bulge before gaining the big ledge and executing a thoughtful top out.

name: Layback Snack
description: Climb the second, right angling crack.

name: Skippin' Breakfast
description: Alternate start to Layback Snack. SDS beneath the small overhang with a key undercling pocket. Gun for the crack and ride it to the top

name: Crack Shack
description: Start matched on the ledge, climb the crack (tight fists/wide hands).

name: One Move Wonder
description: Stand start with two tiny crimps and even smaller feet. Use two perfect pockets to float through the high-angle section and up to 15 feet of well-earned, low-angle victory slab. An absolute must do for the Marquette climber.

name: Slaberghasted
description: Starting with right hand in an undercling, climb comfy edges and ledges to the top.

name: A Rat
description: Stand start and climb the arête to a slopey top out.

name: Crack Traverse
description: Starting in the far left of the overhang, traverse left across large ledges to the right angling crack. Ride the crack to a large ledge. Top out or drop. Often wet.

name: Dazed and Confused
description: SDS with double underclings. Move up and compress the arête to gain the jug. Match and drop. Full top out is slabby, blank and still a project.

name: Moss Boss
description: SDS matched in the slot with feet under the bulge. Climb horizontal edges to the top.

name: Pull Out or Bleed
description: Stand start on two side pulls. Moderate techy climbing leads to a powerful and scary sequence to the lip. Highball.

name: The Rail Project
description: Start matched on the massive slot. An epic gymnastic sequence with two huge moves and arguably the best hold in the UP lies beneath a huge and heady top out with sparse holds. Still has yet to see an ascent. Another slightly harder version traverses in from the left on small edges.

name: Sketchbook
description: Technical climbing on ledges with varying levels of positivity leads to a thoughtful top out.

name: Splash Zone
description: Start matched on a low edge. Climb left finishing on the end of the crack traverse

name: Tarzan
description: SDS low and left. Ride the sweet rail feature to more big ledges and a mantle top out. If only it were taller...

name: Tarzan's Crack
description: Sit start and climb the crack into the top section of Tarzan

name: Topless
description: Begin matched on low crimp rail with heel hook. Pull up right to slopey side pull and throw for the lip.

name: Hollywood Highball
description: Horiziontal holds center line lead to the top of this face.

name: Road Warior
description: Super fun route with a nice balance start on small footholds up a steep slab then into some easy terrian that joins the finish of "turning a corner"

name: Turning a Corner
description: Follow the corner from it's lowest point and turn the lip at the top. Slightly highball with not the best landing use caution .

name: Cat & Mouse
description: Two beautiful traditional climbs separated by a large ledge that can be linked up as a little multi-pitch adventure. Fun, well protected, moderate climbing with great summit views of Lake Superior and all the peaks of 550.Pitch 1: Climb the jagged, right angling crack. Big feature climbing with crack protection and comfortable stances. A beautiful line. Anchor off the Red Pine just left of the top out. 50' 5.5.Pitch 2: From the top of pitch 1, walk right about 30' to the dihedral crack system with several stepped overhangs. A little more technical and airy than pitch 1, some smaller holds, stemming, and a few mantles will bring you to a bolted anchor at the top. Big thanks to Brandon Snyder for installing the bolts and saving many future anchor building headaches 50' 5.6.

name: Beginner's Luck
description: Start with two side pulls, climb the high-angle slab and top out. Detached blocks are off.

name: Chipper
description: Start crouched with left and on a side-pull/undercling and right in a finger lock. Without using detached blocks or the ramp behind, gain the lip and execute an awkward mantle. A bit contrived.

name: Crack Roof Left
description: Start low in the dihedral and climb the crack.

name: Crack Roof Right
description: Start on side pulls with good feet, stand into the roof and climb the shallow crack.

name: Down Under
description: Start as for Crack Roof Left but traverse right, staying under the roof, and topping out.

name: Fumbling
description: Starting with a side pull and poor feet, climb the face.

name: Killer Piller
description: Start as low as possible compressing the pillar. Climb big ledges to the top.

name: Unnamed
description: Start matched on a side pull, climb the face to a techy mantle.

name: A-Frame Arête
description: Stand start, climb the arête.

name: Crunchy Royale
description: SDS with right hand on the lowest sloper rail and left on a poor side pull. A powerful yet tenuous sequence on improbable holds leads to an unfortunately dabby section just before the top out.

name: Crunchy Royale Direct
description: SDS with right hand on the prominent sloper rail and left on a sloping edge under the roof. Climb straight out and over the bulge, top out.

name: Fruit Ninja
description: Stand start matched on the undercling, gain the big side pull before executing a fun top out.

name: King's Move
description: SDS with both hands on the pink flake. Gain the big side-pull before employing some body positioning to gain the lip and top out.

name: Panini Press
description: Stand start matched on the prominent ledge. Mantle and top out.

name: Pawned
description: Start matched on the prominent ledge. Make a big move with poor feet, gaining the in-cut crack feature. Top out.

name: Sensei's Slab
description: Stand start from two small side pulls, use two small dishes and tiny footholds to make it to the lip. Be sure to stay in the center of the face, don’t wander to the arête!

name: Slippery When Wet
description: Start on two slopey edges. Make powerful moves to on slopey ledges before topping out.

name: The Annex
description: SDS compressing a ledge on the left and slot rail on the right. Climb the short, gently overhung face and top out. If only it were twice the size...

name: The Beast Low
description: SDS with a side-pull rail for the right and a sloper for the left. 2 powerful moves lead into the regular start.

name: The Beast
description: Stand start both hands on a small ledge, climb the face and top out.

name: Classic Crack
description: Nice high ball crack, jugs at the top

name: Colossus of Clout
description: Start with side pulls above head height. Delicately climb the face and top out.

name: Home Run Project
description: Start crouched with a sloper in the left and crimpy undercling in the right. Climb the sparsely featured face. Big moves, scary and sequential. This climb has been attempted but not completed.

name: L7 Weenie
description: A short section of hand-sized crack leads to ledgy climbing and a top out. Sketchy landing.

name: Moss Jam
description: Stem up a small recess and moss jam it up to the top

name: Panic Disorder
description: Eliminate. Climb The Xanax without using the adjacent wall on the left.

name: Peffercorn
description: SDS with underclings beneath the prominent bulge. A pleasing sequence through neat features leads to the top out. Would surely achieve classic status if the rock quality wasn't so questionable.

name: Smalls
description: SDS compressing the arête on the left and a sloper on the right. More technical compression leads to a slopey top out.

name: Smalls Left
description: SDS with a crimp on the arête for the right and the crack for the left. Climb the arête to a slopey top out.

name: Squints
description: Stand start, climb the broken crack. Questionable rock quality.

name: Titan of Terror Project
description: Starting with the prominent undercling, climb the face. Attempted but not completed. Poor landing.

name: The Xanax
description: Stand start with a crimp on the right arête and a side pull near the adjacent face. Ride the slopey lip into the dihedral and top out.

name: Yeah Yeah
description: SDS with hands in the crack. Strenuous laybacking leads to the top out.

name: Kalley's Slab
description: Start crouched with right hand on a good sidepull crimp and left on a micro crimp. Climb the slab. Surprisingly fun and engaging with a gorgeous top out view.

name: Slip n' Slide
description: Start matched on the large ledge, climb the dihedral.

name: Stop, Top, & Roll
description: Stand start matched on the large edge. Head left, surfing flat ledges with poor feet before topping out at the apex of the boulder.

name: Tip Top
description: Start matched on the prominent ledge, bust out to slopers on the lip and top out.

name: Top Notch
description: Start matched on the thin crimp rail. Head left into a small pinch. Tenuous foot moves and a small dish lie beneath a heady top out.

name: Topper
description: SDS with left hand on an edge and right on an obvious flake. Compress slopers and slots to the top.

name: Topsy Turvy
description: Start matched on the thin crimp rail. Head right to a big sidepull/pinch before searching for the key hold above the lip that guards the top out.

name: Antiquated
description: Sit start as far right as possible in the crack. Follow the crack as it zig-zags through the overhang and up the face.

name: Antiquated Left
description: Start as low as possible in the crack as for Antiquated. Upon reaching the end of the overhang, trend left to the big ledge and top out from there.

name: Arrowhead
description: SDS matched on a rail. Make some strenuous bumps to gain the arête before riding it to the top.

name: Bag Lunch
description: Stand start with two left-facing underclings. Move up to a thumbercling and a sloper before gunning for the top out jug. Cool grips with an awkwardly close tree.

name: Crosswalk
description: Stand start matched on the prominent ledge. Delicately high step your way to the top. Detached blocks are off.

name: Heirloom
description: Stand start matched on a ledge feature. Climb up the large, detached pillar on more ledges and in-cuts. Top out. Fun climbing at an attention-grabbing height.

name: New Age
description: SDS with a left hand pinch and a small, extruded, two-finger knob for the right. Employ some compression to gain the pinch complex above head height before heading for the big break above and topping out.

name: Tessellate
description: Stand Start with two low, small edges. Climb up the rounded dome on interesting, small features before topping out.

name: Jump the Shark
description: This is a must do for anyone wanting to push into some reasonable highball moves. The crux comes low and with a sloping landing the comitment level is just right.

name: Sharks Fin
description: Climb the right side of the fin

name: Top of the world crack
description: The route starts in an diagonal seam that works up and right to vertical cracks the top is face climbing on jugs.

name: Double cracks
description: hand crack boulder climb

name: Sun Slab
description: Climb the two flared seams

name: Death Grips
description: SDS with a sloping edge for the left and in-cut side pull for the right. Climb left through the arête feature, compressing cool edges before topping out as for Jukebox Hero.

name: Jukebox Hero
description: Arguably one of the most aesthetic lines in Marquette has to offer. SDS with a left hand finger lock and right in a big slot/ledge. Compress the gorgeous prow before trending left through big ledges and scrambling to the top. Great movement on an epic feature. Classic.

name: East Face solo
description: the route consists of four mini pitches. the first is a slab followed by a overhang with a good crack try to avoid the loose flake when the crack goes to fingers, the 3rd section is a stem up a corner, this corner is visible from the trail and is helpful in finding the route. the 4th section follows cracks directly to the summit

name: Leaning Corner
description: Climb the obvious crack in the back of the left leaning corner

name: Hogwart crack
description: Short crack on the Hogwart with two varaiotions. Not very tall but a good beginer route to teach how to lead short routes safely.

name: MudSlide
description: Just like the aproach trail this one is usually pretty dirty! With more traffic this could become a great beginer lead.

name: North Country Corner
description: This is a fairly stright forward climb. Obvious left facing corner that starts about 10ft up the wall. Takes good small cams for the lead

name: The Finger Crack
description: purest finger crack in the UP

name: Ham Stack
description: Stand start matched on the big ledge. Climb up through similar features and top out. A sit start is possible, but wouldn't contribute much.

name: Hanging with Hornets
description: Many variations possible on thin slabs leading to a pull through an overhang. The lead is slightly run out at the bottom but has a solid stance to place the first pice of gear

name: Hogs Tooth
description: There are four ways to this climb this route. The crux on all is the virticle step and evey varaition goes at the same grade

name: pig roast
description: short hands crack

name: Pulled Pork
description: SDS with right hand on a low side pull and left on an undercling. Climb up, compressing neat in-cuts before toping out. Cool grips!

name: Swine Flu
description: Obvious crack that leads to a small ledge with a block on it. Bottom is wet a lot of times but easy going moves that lead to good gear. Crux is where the finger crack starts to lead to hands.

name: Too Many Lady Bugs
description: This is the most striking line on hogback! Starting up a a steep wall with a series of nice holds launch into an overhaning stem using the tips crack to pull into the fantastically unlikley stem. Lieback into a kneelock rest at the top of the overhang then either crimp stright up, or launch backwards to a deadpoint cross and mantle onto the "jug" rail. Both varaitions are similar in difficulty and provind a rest stance at the top of the overhang. The funs not over yet!!! finish on a slightly overhanging seam and pull right over the lip.

name: Backside of Joe’s Roof
description: Start on far right side on a crack/edge. Move up arete and top out.

name: Bay boulder
description: This boulder is the first encounted when walking east around the point

name: The Birthplace of Fred and George
description: Easy slab. There are two possible routes on this boulder, one that follows a slight bump up to the right, and one that goes to the left. The one on the left starts with two underclings on two ridges, about arms length apart.

name: Blocky/Flakey Highball Boulder
description: Start on low ledge and work your way up good face holds and sidepulls. Tall and heady but not very difficult.

name: Center Boulder
description: Start low on left side. Work way up thing crimps and arete to top out of view of Wetmore/Hidden Beach areas.

name: Crack Boulder
description: High ball finger to hands crack

name: Devils staircase
description: This is the old rock the climbs are on the 3rd stair from the top and start in horizontal holds

name: East Side Deep Water Boulder
description: On the east side, there are several good lines for deep water boulder problems. There are at least 5-6 distinct lines in this area. Depending on how wet hands, shoes, and holds are, most are in the V0-V3 range.

name: Highball Slab
description: One of the most aesthetic problems in MQT. It is slightly less than vert. Start on obvious crimp edge. Move up thin crimps to top. LZ is complex and needs 3-4 pads to make for a good landing zone.

name: Highball Slab Boulder - north arete
description: SDS. Start with right hand low on blocky side pull and left had on small side pull. Move up arete using corner and face holds. Finish at ledge and traverse right to escape.

name: Joe’s Roof
description: Local test piece. Stout overhanging granite. Start on obvious crimp. Move out to lip and top out.

name: Joe’s Roof Area - Boulder to SW
description: SDS with left hand low in side pull and right hand on side pull. Move up crimps and sidepulls to top out.

name: Joe’s Roof Area - Boulder to SW - Right face
description: SDS with left hand on crimp and right hand on small side pull. Work your way up on crimps and side pulls. Top out and walk down slab.

name: Joe’s Roof Area - lowball Boulder to SE
description: Short but fun moves. Start low on blocky sidepull feature. Move out to arete and up.

name: Joe’s Roof Area - Pocket Boulder
description: Depending on season, might have water under it. Start on two small holds with a high foot, and make big move to an awesome two finger pocket. Move up and top out.

name: Oval Boulder on East Side
description: Start low and left utilizing only this boulder. climb up crimps and slopers to top out.

name: Pinacle rock
description: There are alot of routes on this rock. one up the pinacle two cracks behind the pinacle and two faces

name: Pinnacle Face
description: To the left of the Pinnacle Boulder is a clean granite face. There are 2-3 unique lines on the face. On the left, is the hardest line. Start on a good ledge and make big move to jug. Move up and top out from there. In the middle, with a stand start, climb up staying left of flake. Good holds to the top. To the right of the flake is the easiest line. These are approximately V2-, V0, and Veasy.

name: Water crack
description: Nice finger crack

name: The Wedge Boulder
description: Start on head height edge, get a high foot, and make a few easy but fun moves to top.

name: West Side Deep Water - Roof Route
description: Fun line up a cool overhang feature. This one is borderline deep enough. Shallowest spot is about 40 inches. Need to have good awareness how you fall, or don't fall.

name: West Side Deep Water Boulders
description: On the west side of the island, next to an easy access ramp into the lake, there is an aesthetic cliff that is slightly overhanging. Grades are hard when you are wet and holds are wet. Water is deep enough to take a fall (5 feet and deeper). The right line starts with right hand on a good pinch and left hand on a crimp. Move out right to a sidepull and up. The left line starts anywhere on a long crimp rail. Climb up small crimps, or make a big, and very fun, move to the lip. For summer days, lots of variations here. This is near the Pinnacle Boulder.

name: Ghost Train
description: Fun adventure climbing on clean granite makes this a must do for anyone looking to experience 550 climbing in all its beauty. The route takes 9 bolts up clean slab climbing into a small overhang that puts you on the pitch one ledge with a two bolt anchor(no rings). From there 5 bolts lead out onto another clean slab with nice exposure to ring anchors at the top. A 60m rope will touch base if rappelling in or to pull ropes. If setting a top rope from the rings use a redirect on the first pitch anchors. The route can also be lead in one long pitch with one long runner at pitch one anchors 15 draws and anchor material.

name: Acer Facer
description: Climb left face of detached boulder.

name: Chockstone Route
description: Start in the cave beneath the chockstone and work our way out to an arete. Pass the overhang into a shallow right faceing corner and finish in the crack

name: Just Another Maple Monday
description: Right arete of detached block.

name: Moosewood Crack
description: Climb to the crack, climb the crack to the flake, past the piton to the top.

name: Sliced Bread
description: Follow a left facing corner with two cracks on the left face

name: Survival of the Fitness
description: This route starts in the crack formed by the boulder laying aginst the base of the cliff then traverses along the lip of the boulder as far as you can go then tops out

name: Flying Frog Roof
description: This route is short and sweet and has some fantastic moves on it. For the lead bring several crash pads and spotters to protect the first section to the stopper placement. It's a good idea to toprope the route first and work out the sequence as it's very specific thru the roof. An onsight would be super impressive on this one!! The entire route is left of Rays Bomb-Garden Crack but shares the same last move and protection.

name: Rays Bomb-Garden
description: This route takes the crack in the corner through overhangs and finishes on the finger crack at the top

name: Wam Up Crack
description: Fun low angle crack

name: Bonsai Pipeline
description: One of the tallest climbs on sugarloaf! Gear is good but a bit runout! Avoid the block pulling into the crux by traversing low and looking for a horiziontal placment that is really solid. From there climb stright up left of the bonsai pine!!

name: Bubblegum Knife Party
description: Sit start under the overhang and reach for a nice hold, undercling the mini roof and go for the knife!! Folow the blade to the top.

name: Dark Skies
description: Just left of schoolhouse Ridge is dark Skies. Five bolts lead to a two bolt anchor. The route can also be led to the rap rings for schoolhouse Ridge if you're looking to top out and pull ropes.

name: Garbage Food for Garbage People
description: Stand start on a flat ledge. Compress crimps and slopers before gunning for the lip. Technical and scrunchy.

name: How High??
description: Good crack climb just a little to high for most to boulder. Start by scrambling to a small ledge where the crack starts and fire up to the top!!

name: Intrusion
description: SDS compressing the double arête feature. Climb up and right with fa few thuggy moves to the lip. Top out.

name: Midnight Run
description: More moderate climbing up a gully area of the main cliff. Starts on a small ground level ledge and tend left. 6 bolts to top rope anchors this can also be led to the rappel rings for this side of the cliff if you want to top out and pull ropes. The second option requires 7 draws.

name: The Rhino
description: Start crouched on two crimps, head left into the large ledge before shooting up through flat edges and then the lip. Top out.

name: Schoolhouse Ridge
