description: This is a great route for the new leader. Fun moderate climbing with just enough space between bolts to sharpen your lead head.

name: Trash Monger
description: Stand start with a left hand side-pull and right hand at the lip. Trend left and up the prow feature on edges and slopers. A bit contrived.

name: Water streak down
description: Fun slab climbing short but sweet! This route is often wet and better later in the day after receiving some sun.

name: We want a shrubbery
description: There are a few variations but all follow the bolt line either left center or right. 7 bolts and anchors. This can be led to the rappel rings with 8 draws to pull ropes.

name: The Altruist
description: SDS with right hand pinch and left hand gaston. Slopey edges and some high stepping defends the top out.

name: Copepod
description: SDS as for Daphnia, but upon reaching the right angling sloping rail head right toping out in the slight dihedral.

name: The Crawl
description: Stand start with a left hand pocket and small right hand tooth. Climb the up the slab using sloping ledges and cool pockets.

name: Daphnia
description: SDS on a low rail. Climb up into the right angling sloping ledge before moving left and topping out.

name: Death by Dihedral
description: Stand start in on the face just left of the roof. Climb the dihedral till you reach the prominent crack. Layback and follow the crack up and around a bulge before topping out. Excellent climb, bad landing. The freestanding block behind you is off!

name: Deliverance
description: Start crouched with opposed slopers and poor feet. A few heady moves lead to a milder top out.

name: Former
description: SDS on a matched on a protruding block. Climb similar positive features to the top.

name: Handicap Ramp
description: SDS matched on an in-cut flake, climb positive ledges before mantling on to the ramp and topping out.

name: Hold Onto Your Carhartts
description: An awkward start with two sidepulls leads to mellower climbing and a top out. Adjacent left wall is off

name: Jugly Duckling
description: SDS on two side pulls compress positive edges to the top. Rock quality is questionable, landing is sketchy.

name: Latter
description: SDS on a triangle feature, climb positive in-cuts before reaching the top out.

name: Modern Marvel
description: Start Crouched with right hand low on the arête  and left on a small edge. Climb the arête before sneaking left under the roof and topping out. Fun movement with an awkward landing and poor position. All detached blocks and adjacent walls are off.

name: Modernity
description: Start low on the arête. Some laybacking on poor feet leads to a slopey top out.

name: Post Modern
description: Stand start, layback the arête and top out. All detached blocks and adjacent walls are off.

name: Postcard
description: Start with right hand on the arête and left on a small edge. A few delicate moves lead to the top.

name: Ramparts
description: SDS matched on a slanting in-cut, climb the arete-like feature of the ramp till you reach the top.

name: Right of Way
description: SDS on the largest in-cut in the center of the face. Climb edges and slots to the top. Watch out for loose blocks as you near the top out.

name: Rotifer
description: SDS on a nice in-cut before climbing through more positive ledges to the top. Nice grips, short but sweet.

name: Self Service
description: SDS with a right hand edge and whatever you can find for the left. Slab it out. Questionable rock quality.

name: Serendipitously
description: SDS low on the big flake. Ride tasty side pulls to the top!

name: Sinking feeling
description: Right under the down tree that leans on the boulder. Start with a right handed under cling/crimp and a left hand on a full pad crimp. Not quite a sit start. Reach up with the right to a V shaped crimp. Bring your right foot up and drop the left. Grab a slope-y pinch with the left at hip level to stabilize and then bump it up to a crimp matching the right. Lock off to bring your feet up. Stand up reaching for sloped crimp (crux move). Then either lock off if you are stable enough or a dyno to a sloper top to the right of the crack. Finish with a top out or call it good. I won’t judge.

name: Stage Right
description: SDS with a side pull for the right and left wherever is comfortable, climb positive edges to the top. Detached blocks are off.

name: Stepwise
description: Stand start with right hand on the arête at waist heigth and left on a slopey triangular cutout. Techy and progressively easier slab climbing leads to the top out.

name: Stepwise SDS
description: SDS with the two mini triangle pockets. Climb left and up on poor holds topping out as for Stepwise.

name: Strut
description: Start matched on a rail, climb up the slab using sloping edges.

name: That Chossy Good for Nothing Traverse
description: SDS all the way left on a big ledge and sidepull. Traverse left, topping out just before the outcrop ends. Questionable rock quality.

name: Trail Booger
description: SDS with a side pull for the left and the large sloping ledge in the right. Climb the arete. Very technical. Body positions are kind of scrunched, may be easier if you’re short.

name: Trail roof
description: Two ways to climb the crack, the easier starts off the block, the other traverses in from the right

name: Trail Spice
description: SDS matched on a positive block, gain the big slot and climb excellent edges to the top. Great sequence!

name: Undercling Thing
description: Sit start with a side-pull and ledge, climb right, to the key undercling. Toss for the sloper and top out.

name: Waffles and Wifi
description: Start with double gastons at head height. Move left to a flake before topping out. Fun sequence.

name: Warm-up Center Traverse
description: Start as for Stage Right and traverse left topping out on Latter or start as for Latter, traverse right and top out on (aka exit) Stage Right.

name: Bourgeois
description: SDS matched on the prominent rail in the center of the overhang. Head out right to a side-pull crimp before gaining the prow. Employ some exciting footwork to surmount the lip and top out. A short climb with powerful, gymnastic movement. Classic!

name: Hook
description: SDS with left hand side pull and right hand on another side pull. Climb right, into the middle section of pan and top out.

name: Left Entry
description: SDS with right hand on an edge and left on a small side pull/pinch. Come in to a left hand pinch and blast to a jug. Top out.

name: Painfully Obvious
description: SDS with both hands on a the large undercling. Muscle up to a decent edge before heading right to similar edges and topping out. A bit dabby in some parts, but an excellent climb nonetheless!

name: Pan
description: SDS with right hand on an undercling edge and left on a positive ledge. Climb large edges to the top.

name: Papyrifera
description: Lay-down start. Left hand on a large ledge and right in an incut triangle-jug. Move left to an incut ledge before highstepping with small edges in hand. Would be considerably less awkward without the birch tree right behind you, nice movement though. Detached blocks are off!

name: Right Entry
description: SDS on a slightly incut edge in the center of the overhang. Move left to a side pull and then bump to a large ledge. Climb positive holds to the top.

name: Crack block
description: The direct line going up the crack is solid, one more line follows the arete to the right on face holds

name: Crack Block Direct
description: SDS as you would to climb the crack, but head straight up, using holds on the arete and face.

name: Crack Block Indirect
description: Sit start directly below the crack on slopey crimps. Gain the crack and top out.

name: Crack Block Left
description: SDS at the left arete with no detached blocks for feet. Climb the arete to the top

name: Crack Block Right
description: SDS with a side pull crimp for the left and sloping vertical rail in the right. Climb up and right through blocky features before riding the arete to the top. No detached blocks for feet.

name: Crack Block Slab
description: SDS on a large ledge, climb the slab. Nice holds with good movement!

name: Da Slab
description: Sit start with a left hand side pull and right hand pinch. Climb the slab

name: Jam Arete
description: SDS. Climb the arete. All detached blocks are off.

name: Jam Boulder Left
description: SDS on an undercling flake. Gain the arete and ride it to the top

name: The jam boulder
description: The route climbs center face on good holds to a hand jam at the top

name: Jam Slab Center
description: Start crouched on the obvious ramp. Stand up and use a dirty crack and good feet to walk up the slab.

name: Jam Slab Left
description: SDS. Stand up into some interesting thumberclings befor heading for the lip.

name: Jam Slab Right
description: SDS with a big incut in the right hand and left wherever is comfortable. Climb the arete. Detached blocks are off!

name: Ledge block and traverse boulder
description: on the ledge block there is four routes, the finest of these starts off small sidepulls center face and moves up and right. traverse boulder has one route and moves from a sit right to left follow the obvious line and top out along the way

name: Left Overhang
description: When the water is low, the left overhang can be climbed

name: Overhang Arête
description: Sit start with a slopey pinch for the right and a nearby crimp for the left. Climb the arête.

name: Right of Right Overhang
description: Start on two side-pulls, gain a sharp slot then head for the lip and top out.

name: Right Overhang
description: Sit start on the big ledge. Gain the crack, then head left before surmounting the bulge and topping out.

name: Right Overhang Direct
description: Start matched on the big undercling. Work through crimps before taking on the bulge and topping out.

name: Tapered Crack
description: Sit start from the big ledge. Gain and climb the tapered crack.

name: Unnamed
description: sit start, head straight up the nice ledges

name: Water block
description: There are three lines on this block, the most quality route is on the north side, the most sketchy but very good route climbs out over the really bad fall into the water FA:Zack Knoteck   line 3 takes the thin seam on the south side of the block also bad water landing

name: The Big Lonely
description: SDS with a left hand mini-pinch and a right hand side-pull. Make a huge move to a triangular sloper/pinch (the left hand start hold of lush) before compressing the arête to gain the victory jug and topping out. Detached features are off.

name: Big Rainbow
description: Starts off at a crack near the bottom of boulder, follow this crack up until you make a big move with left hand to a triangular slope, then move right hand to grab vertically flat crack. The left hand then moves left to a large crimp and the right hand moves up to a crimp. Big Left hand move up to a jug and match this hold. From here traverse left grabbing a sloper with the left hand then a crimp with right so you can move the left hand to a pinch and then bump it to a jug. Match this jug and finally there are two more jug holds to top out.

name: The Burbot
description: Link Ling Cod into Lota Lota. The length and movement of this climb make it very enjoyable!

name: The Butcher
description: SDS with right hand on a positive side-pull and left on the sloping ledge. Move left along the ledge before rocking over to grab a very sharp but positive rail and topping out.

name: Cave of the Dreaming Bear
description: Start matched in the giant flake/crack as far down at left in the slot cave as you can manage. Traverse left following the crack until it goes vertical. Head up with it and top out. Sustained and sharp.

name: Cleaver
description: Start as for butcher but climb straight up through huge in-cuts.

name: Couriers du Bois
description: SDS with left hand in the seam and right on a side-pull/undercling feature. Head up and slightly left through a series of stellar grips to a thought provoking top out. It's not possible to protect this climb with the current water levels, exercise caution.

name: Cusk
description: SDS with left hand on a small incut and right on a tiny three-finger crimp. Make a powerful move to gain the big holds of Lota Lota and top out.

name: Double Scoup
description: Start squating on a low block. Work up big ledges before moving left to a large side-pull feature after which delicate movement on sloping crimps leads to a thoughtful top-out

name: Eelpout
description: SDS with a low ledge for the left and an incut edge for the right. Climb Diagonal crimps to the top.

name: Eelpout Low
description: Laydown Start with left hand on an edge and right on a low side-pull. Use some core strength to keep your but off the pads as you gain the start crimper of Eelpout and ride its nice crimps to the top.

name: Instant Oats
description: Climb the center of the tall slab, don't fall

name: Lakeshore Overhang
description: SDS with a side pull in the left and a slopey ledge for the right. Compression on blocky holds leads to an awkward top out.

name: Lawyer
description: SDS with a left hand side-pull and right hand gaston. Make a powerful move to a stellar quartz pocket before gaining the lip and topping out as for Lota Lota.

name: Ling Cod
description: SDS with a small pocket in the left and a slopey pinch for the right. Climb the arête using small edges and blocky pinches. Top out straight over the lip.

name: Loche
description: Stand-start with left hand on the arête and right on a small crimp. Establish and toss for the lip. There is potential for a lower start, but it would be much more difficult.

name: Loche Low
description: Lay-down Start with left hand on the arête and right on a slopey, side-pull crimp. Muster up some body tension as you work through a series of crimps to gain the start of the dead-point. Top out as for Loche.

name: Lota Lota
description: Stand/jump start on the lip at the far right end of the boulder. Traverse left on positive edges and pockets topping out at the other end of the boulder. Excellent holds with thoughtful movement.

name: Lush
description: Stand start with a left hand on a sloper and right hand a horizontal pinch above head height. Gain a couple in-cuts and power over the bulging lip to a mellow top out slab.

name: Methy
description: Start as for Eelpout Low, but cross into an undercling crimp and head left through a few edges before manteling at the lip and topping out.

name: Mizayikaa
description: SDS with left hand on an undercling and right on a side-pull edge. Work up the steep face with some fancy foot work before executing the crux throw and topping out on the slab above.

name: Mud Shark
description: SDS with right hand on a side-pull deep in the cave and right compressing a large in-cut side-pull. Tension your way to the wave-polished sloper before pulling the bulge and topping out.

name: Pays D'en Haute
description: Sit start matched on the prominent rail. Balance up the high-angle face to a mantel top out.

name: Phat Phish
description: Start sitting in the whole where "The Poverty Line" starts. Chimney the first half using detached blocks then climb the face to the top. Awkward start in the slot.

name: Poor Man's Lobster
description: Start sitting partly in the hole matched on an undercling. Gain the large ledge before trending right and making the powerful crux move to a far away edge and topping out.

name: Pork Eater
description: SDS with right hand on a sloping crimp and left on a three-finger edge. Traverse left into The Butcher using positive edges and nonexistent feet. Rather dabby...

name: Pork Rinds
description: Start as for Pork Eater but top out early and right using a large ledge.

name: The Poverty Line
description: The low start to Poor Man's Lobster. Start sitting in the hole on two edges. 5 moves, just enough to zap some power, stand between you and the start of Poor Man's Lobster. A sequential, power endurance block that would surely be classic if it weren't so awkwardly dabby. All detached blocks are off!

name: Presidential
description: SDS matched low on the arête. Follow the lip of the boulder, utilizing some poor footholds, before topping out on the far left end.

name: The Scoup Low
description: SDS in the back of the cave matched on an undercling. Using small crimps work through the steep bulge to into the start of The Scoup. Nice movement, but a bit dabby. Detached blocks are off.

name: The Scoup Traverse
description: One of the best traverse routes on the lakeshore. The scoup traverse sit starts far right and takes the lip of the cave into the original scoup route on the left

name: The Scoup
description: SDS on the lowest jug, make big moves on more positive edges before topping out

name: Spineless Catfish
description: Start as for Mizayikaa (right hand side-pull, left hand undercling) and climb left, executing a crux throw to gain the start of Lush. Top out as for lush. Pleasing and sustained movement, but slightly dabby.

name: Trail Slab
description: Start crouched, climb the left side of the slabby face to a top out.

name: Unnamed
description: Left hand on three finger (one pad) sidepull and right hand on 2-3 finger (one pad) sidepull. Move out to arete and up. Good movement.

name: Fructose
description: SDS matched low on the arête. Ride it to the top out.

name: Galactose
description: Start crouched, compressing the overhanging refrigerator feature. A powerful deadpoint leads to the mantel. The ramp below is off.

name: Glucose
description: SDS low on the left side of the boulder. Ride the sloping lip, topping out as for Maltose.

name: Lactose
description: SDS matched on the right end of the lip. Utilize some body tension and traverse left until reaching a sizable in-cut near and mantling it out.

name: Maltose
description: SDS matched on the arête. Climb up, getting into a bit of compression before topping out.

name: Sucrose
description: SDS with left hand on the arête and right on a low side-pull. A powerful move lies between you and the mantel.

name: Xylose
description: SDS with left hand on a side-pull around the arête and right on a low pinch. Compress the blank feature before making a powerful throw at the lip.

name: Cougar Bear
description: This highball climb has some fun overhanging moves low and nice slab moves up high. Start low and head for the jug at the lip. Gain the jug and climb the upper slab to the top.

name: Downclimb Route
description: Used as a downclimb for the main part of the cut but a fun route on the way up as well. Climb up on a easy lieback crack and step left to the top

name: Hang in There
description: It seems tall and unlikley but "hang in there" for the thank god hold at the top passing the overhang

name: Jungle Cat Project
description: Beautiful project that will go with some work. Lots of pads could help the commitment level. Start on the indented hold and move up on small crimps to a over the head lieback.

name: Rail Traverse
description: Follow the obvious rail hold on the backside of the boulder to a slopey top out

name: Tuck Orignal Route
description: Tuck Orginal Route is the fist and as of this posting only route in the area. It follows the overhang on small holds into the backbend tuck move out the roof then cut loose and hold on!! This route then traverses right out of the roof around the corner and vertical for another 15ft.

name: Boogie Man
description: SDS back in the overhang matched on a horizontal crack. Climb out right through crimps before making a crux move to a ledge before climbing the face and topping out.

name: Brandon's Crack
description: SDS, climb the thin crack and top out.

name: Cinnamon and Sage
description: Start crouched on edges, climb the slab and top out. An aesthetic line.

name: Dream Eater
description: SDS matched in a horizontal crack in back of the roof. Follow the crack up and left through the overhang. Top out above.

name: In the Moonlight
description: Stand start, compressing the double arête feature with feet on the ramp below. Climb up the tall blocky face on great features. Highball.

name: Mondo
description: SDS compressing the overhanging fridge feature, squeeze your way up before trending left and topping out. A powerful and sequential moderate. Classic.

name: Ominous Wind
description: SDS matched low on the sloping arête. Work up the sloping feature to a crux dead point before heading up big ledges and toping out. The ramp on the left side of the overhang is off.

name: Meeting of the Minds
description: SDS on undercling flake, move left set up deadpoint to best sloper in Michigan. Continue left and top out above.

name: Mind Control
description: Stand start with left hand crimp, right hand sloper, dynamic to edge, flake features to top. Potential for hard but awkward sit start.

name: Bathos
description: Start crouched matched on an edge. A few delicate moves lead to the lip.

name: Bog Eye
description: SDS and climb the splitter hand crack to top out.

name: Cotton Grass
description: Stand start matched on a crimp, work up the face on thin holds with good feet. Grab the lip and top out. The crack is off.

name: Funk-Fried
description: SDS with a pinch in the left hand and a slopey crimp in the right. Work up the arête, then devise a solution to get out from under the bulge and gain the lip. Cryptic.

name: Rhododendron
description: Start crouched with a left hand on a sloper and right hand low on the arête. Balance up the slab and top out.

name: Rosemary
description: SDS on a large pinch. Layback a small crack before heading up the face and topping out. Nice moves on great holds, unfortunately the tree is practically scratching your back for the last half of the climb.

name: Agent of Entropy
description: SDS with a thin left hand cimper and right on the low but massive undercling feature. A strenuous series of moves on cool holds leads to a thought-provoking top out.

name: Big League Chew
description: SDS with two triangle crimps. A few powerful moves on small holds leads to a top out. It may be short, but it sure packs a punch!

name: Bong Chandelier
description: SDS with both hands in the finger crack. Jam and stem your way through the overhanging dihedral to gain the lip. Head left and top out.

name: Curry, Beer, & Ice Cream
description: SDS matched on the sketchy loose jug that refuses to come out (trust me, I've tried!). Head left then up, through a couple ledges, before topping out. Nice movement.

name: The Golden Winch
description: Sit-start matched in a slot. Pull into the undercling out left before locking off to gain a tiny slot. From here, traverse right over the water on big ledges to top out. Nice rock with great holds and fun movement.To start standing or crouched would drop the grade by at least 1 V-point.

name: Rat Shart
description: SDS on blocky jug and climb the arête, topping out at the apex.

name: Shag Carpet
description: Sit start with two slots. Climb up the face to big ledges and a top out.

name: Extrasensory
description: SDS with a left hand finger lock at the lip and right in the crack below. Work some trickery to worm your way up the overhang to an obnoxiously good two-finger stack before riding big edges to the top out. Tenuous and technical. Bring some tape for this one.

name: Gangster's Paradise
description: Start as for Shindex, but climb right at the lip linking into The Other Side of Paradise. A sequential, power endurance block with a heart breaking last move.

name: Hamster
description: Stand start at far right of the ledge, climb similar features to a top out.

name: Hog Tied
description: Stand start matched on flake a few powerful moves to gain ledges, top out. This one's got a spooky landing situation.

name: L'Appel Du Vide
description: SDS with a sloping dish on the left arête and a low opposing side-pull edge in the right hand. Bump into the rail utilized by the Shindex and execute some burly compression before trending left at the lip and topping out. Powerful, strenuous, and dynamic.

name: The Other Side of Paradise
description: SDS on with both hands on the blocky feature in the center of roof. Head right, into a prow feature, before making a huge dead-point beneath the lip and topping out.

name: Paradise
description: Start on the blocky feature in the front-center of the roof. Head left through a sloper and pinch, topping out as for The Shindex.

name: Peace and Carrots
description: SDS with left hand on side pull, and right on a sloper. Climb flakes and crimps to top.

name: Pig Headed
description: Stand start at far left of ledge, climb left and into the flake, top out.

name: The Shindex
description: Laydown start with both hands on the ledge in the back-center of the roof. Climb out through the overhang on powerful under-clings and slopers before topping out. Bring your biceps for this classic.

name: Broken Candy
description: Begin on the two lowest obvious crimps, and climb straight up the face. Fun powerful moves lead into a barn-door finish on the "love handle."

name: Endless Love Project
description: This project is a low start to Love Handle (V5) which begins on jugs down and right (around the corner) from Love Handle's start holds. Powerful, pumpy, and techy.

name: Middle
description: The left bolted route is the harder of the two routes. Solid 13. Four bolts plus anchors with biners to lower. Gets progressively harder. Good luck.

name: Right
description: This is the rightmost bolted route on the main face. Route is on you from the beginning. Body position dependent beta. Crimps, gastons, side pulls, slopers, and elusive feet.

name: Arêtection
description: SDS low on the arête. A fun sequence climbs through nice slopers with a thought-provoking mantle at the apex.

name: Tenting
description: SDS matched on an in-cut block feature. Climb up and into Arêtection.

name: Death Star
description: A superb compression test-piece with incredible movement. Split grade is given for two variations  Matt originally climbed the route by compressing the double arête feature with left hand on a blocky side-pull, right on a small triangle side-pull, and a knee bar.  The other, slightly harder version starts matched on a blocky ledge on the right arête. Then climbs up a few feet before transitioning to the compression section and topping out. This way adds a few VERY high quality moves and makes the crux slightly harder, but less reachy. It's also more congruent with the sit start.

name: Life After Death Star
description: The sit start to Death Star. SDS with left hand on a blocky undercling and right on an in-cut side-pull. Make an powerful move right to a blocky ledge before heading into the regular sequence of Death Star. Burly and sequential compression. All detached blocks are off for feet (even the very tempting belay ledge right where you want your feet to go).

name: Rebel Scum
description: Start matched on the bulging flake with feet on the block below. Climb up and through a few sloping ledges to the top out.

name: The Trash Compactor
description: Start crouched with hands on the big flake-undercling and feet on the detached block below. Climb out the mini roof on nice ledges and top out.

name: Lady Like
description: Stand start with right hand on an in-cut crimp on the arête and left on an edge. Climb the arête and top out. Techy. Detached blocks are off!  A sit start may be possible, but would be difficult and awkward trying to avoid the detached blocks.

name: Ladyfingers
description: Stand start with a low side-pull edge and a shallow mono-pocket at head height. A nice sequence with sweet grips leads up the face to a mellow top out.

name: Tom Boy
description: Stand start matched on the undercling flake, climb nice ledges to the top. Neat holds.

name: Widow's Crack
description: SDS with underclings in the roof. Surmount the bulge and layback the in-cut crack. Top out.

name: The Woman in the Window
description: SDS with slots under the mini roof. Using the unique fin feature, some fancy footwork, and a little burl will get you over the bulge to the mellow top out.

name: Anaerobic Arete Left
description: Start standing, with left hand on the arete and right wherever is most comfortable. Climb the arete, but transition from the right side to the left side about halfway up. Easier and less committing than the right exit.

name: Anaerobic Arete Right
description: Stand start, with left hand on the arete and right wherever is most comfortable. Climb slopers and small edges keeping the areate on your left.

name: Bog Burial
description: SDS with left hand on a side pull and right on a slopey edge. Stand up and climb through positive ledges to a thought provoking top out.

name: Spruced Up
description: SDS with right hand on side pull and left on a small crimp. Gain a slopey edge and march your feet upward as you enter the slabby dihedral.

name: Tamaracked
description: Stand start, with right hand on a side pull and left on a low small crimp. Fight the barn door and throw for a jug. The grade is height dependent (V1 for tall folks, V2 for short folks)!

name: Tamarjacked
description: SDS with right hand on an incut side pull and left on a triangle edge. Move left to the undercling rail before muscling your way to a decent edge above and topping out. Unsuspectingly burly!

name: Deserted
description: Start crouched with big feet. Climb the slab and top out

name: The Girl from Ipanema
description: Dynamically step into a press with both hands, dyno to a side-pull ledge. A rare comp-style problem.

name: Island Crack
description: Start low, climb the dirty hand-sized crack.

name: Smoke Signals
description: Start standing with an undercling in the left and a small crimper in the right. Climb the slab. There is potential for a sit start.

name: Infamous
description: Stand start withan undercling for the left and the lowest sloper on the arête for the right. Climb more slopers to the top out.

name: Infamous SDS
description: SDS with both hands on the big ledge. Make a powerful move to gain the arête. Climb slopers to the top.

name: Intrinsic
description: SDS with right hand on a big flake and left on a sloping edge. Climb slopey crimps on the face to a top out. Nice movement!

name: Noise Pollution Left
description: SDS match on a side-pull. Climb up and left through big ledges to a top out.

name: Noise Pollution Right
description: SDS matched on a side-pull. Climb up and right through some one-pad crimps to the top out.

name: Playwright
description: Start crouched with underclings, head left though more underclings to the top. Fun sequence!

name: Swamp Donkey
description: Start sitting with hands low on the sharp arête of the large detached block. Head towards the small overhang surmounting it using slopers on the arête.

name: Wolf's Den Crack
description: This crack climb is well protected. Starting thin and flaring to larger size by the top it provides a fun little lead with varied gear.

name: 10. Jolly Green Giant
description: Starts inside of the left facing dihedral/chimney. Climb to a good ledge then utilize both cracks to a somewhat ackward top out. You can TR this climb by climbing Dirty Girl and moving up left to it's anchors.  She's called Green for a reason, do the crag a favor and take a spin on it, it does clean up!

name: 11. Dirty Girl
description: By far the best route of the crag!  Super delicate slab, consistent all the way to the anchors!  Anchors can be accessed by scrambling carefully up right side of slab.

name: 4. Too Many Drugs
description: First line on your left when you come out of the assess gully.  Dihedral/face with a small crack section before ledge.  Staircase to the anchors.

name: 5. Chutes And Ladders
description: The name says it all.  Hope your climbing and mantling on sloping glass holds skills are up to speed.  Gotta nut up a bit on this one!  Still a good route.

name: 6. Tweener
description: Another Chutes And Ladders style route.  Stick clip first bolt.

name: 7. 2 Tons Of Fun
description: More straight forward.  Big incuts, funky slab walk, and chill ending make for a fun adventure.

name: 8. Clip It, Mix It, Or Kiss My @#!
description: A cruxy start up past the 2nd bolt. Pull a bouldery 5.10 start with no feet and clip the bolt (or stick clip). Keep climbing up though the obvious crack, up and right to the chains.

name: 9. The Chicks And The Money
description: Climb up to the ledge to clip the first bolt. Clip up and right of the bolts to a small stance before the crux. Battle up the flaring cracks and face to a stance. Rest up, it ain't in the bag, a bulging top out remains.  Climb the finger crack just left of the 2nd bolt to climb on gear. I am unaware of any assents done on gear but it is highly possible

name: Bombing Trains
description: large obvious flake that could likely be climbed 5.12? Sounds like a drum- I'd avoid this as the whole flake could pop off. Also looks of loose rock I cleaned on rappel.

name: Broken Glass
description: Stand start right crimp and left flat faced hold. Right hand up to sloper. Left hand upside down to finger crack, up to larger holds for top out.

name: Jean-Michel Basquiat
description: Probably the best route at graffiti wall .Starts in obvious crack. Hands move up into crimpy moves. Crux into a right finger pocket and then a good flat-topped hold. A little loose rock at the top but not too bad.  Can be top roped off a couple big pines. This could be done a high boulder as well. Not sure on the rating. maybe harder 5.10. Could possibly be led, but the first pro would be above the crux otherwise you'd deck it.

name: Rustoleum
description: Shares holds with broken glass, but shifted just to the right. Crimps and small feet to start, then gain a right hand up to a finger hold sloping left sort of a gaston, and then right hand again, with or without inching feet up, on the top out. Be careful if topping out as some rocks may be loose.

name: Slam
description: Obvious crack witih large open space. Tons of loose rock here. Dangerous. Avoid.

name: A Stroll in the Yard
description: Climb the short vertical face of broken boulders to gain the easy slab to the top.  Finishes at the large pine tree to climbers right of the “smiling” pine tree.

name: Doin' Time
description: Same start as Walk the Line then move left and up toward the upper overhang that forms the right side of the inverted V notch. Take the overhang directly to tenuous friction on the final slab.

name: Get Busy Livin' or Get Busy Dyin'
description: Start in the same alcove as the beginning of Guilty as Charged on the short vertical face. Climb up several small overhangs, past a blueberry patch on climbers left, and finish just right of the trough.

name: The Green Mile
description: Start in front of the large pine tree, climb the short green slab then pass the small tree three quarters of the way up on the left hand side.  Stay left of the inverted V notch apex of the route Doin’ Time.

name: Guilty as Charged
description: Start in an alcove on the short vertical face. Climb up slabby section, past a blueberry patch on climber’s right, and finish in the large trough.

name: Judgement Day
description: Begin at the boulder that is splotched with white quartz. Climb up to the crimpy slab and finish at the “smiling” Pine tree.

name: Walk The Line
description: Slither the green stuff four feet up to the small ledge by the pine tree then walk the line directly up to the group of three pines at the top of the crag.

name: Left Side Route
description: Fairly continuous crack on left side

name: Right Side Crack
description: Mostly continuous crack on right side

name: 1.  Mystery Jam
description: Mystery Jam is the obvious line at Isabella.  Start on the face to a cruxy throw.  Work your way up to the beautiful crack.  Continue up past a few committing jug moves to easier ground.  The top is marked by a fixed nut and pin.

name: 2.  British Air
description: Middle route on the wall

name: 3.  Welsh Express
description: Right route on the wall.

name: 1.  Bee Sting
description: This route is a fun short crack that goes from fingers to fists that has a decent number of face holds. The crack starts out on a large block and then gradually gets wider at the top.

name: 10.  Open Book
description: The route is the off width crack in a dihedral. It starts with wide fists and eventually widens in to a chimney.

name: 11.  Grid Iron Left
description: Left side of slab.

name: 12.  Grid Iron Right
description: Right side of slab.

name: 13.  Red Roof
description: Starts 15' left of the Big Chimney.  Head straight up to an overhanging alcove.  Continue straight up out of the alcove to the top.

name: 14.  Four Star Arete
description: Start 5' left of Big Chimney.  Climb straight up till you hit the roof.  Exit a little left of center through roof and weave through another more manageable roof to anchors just over the top.

name: 15.  Unnamed
description: Wall just right of Big Chimney.  Multiple ways to weave up through the face.  Long and scenic.

name: 16.  Garden Walk
description: Same start as #17 except when the crack Y's take the left crack around the arete.  Trends up and left most of the way until the last bit when you head straight up for the topout.

name: 17.  Pump'n the Gardner
description: One of the furthest climbs to the right, this is a popular crack. Mainly top roped, is a great trad lead as well. Start up the easy 5th class ramp to an off width. The crack splits, climb right. There are crux sections, have fun! Then climb up to easier ground.

name: 18. Golden Light
description: Start up a left leaning ramp into sustained, technical climbing through a couple bulges to a crux near the top.

name: 2.  Unknown left crack
description: Just the the left of unknown crack, where the crack splits tend left.  Climb up to 3rd class and to a roof.  Go right, left, or straight...the choice is yours

name: 3.  Unknown right crack
description: Starts 5' right of route #2 and ends up merging with route #2 at 2/3 height.

name: 5.  Triangle Spire
description: The slabby east side of the spire.

name: 6.  Herr Nightingale
description: Left leaning fingers to hand crack that zig back right a bit then straight to the top.

name: 7.  That was Zen, This is Tao
description: Classic.  Consistently hard.

name: 8.  Lucky Corner
description: This route climbs a flake on the left side of a dihedral for twenty feet. Then the route climbs a few small ledges heading into two small roofs. Climb around the left of the first roof and then to the right of the second roof ending at the rap rings.

name: 9.  Lucky Seven
description: 10 feet right of #8.  Head up and right only to traverse hard left just under a small roof.  Exit on the left side of the roof and punch it straight to the top.

name: Disco Lemonade
description: Start crouched with an undercling for the left hand and large edge for the right. Climb the arête, topping out just shy of the apex.

name: Disco Superfly
description: Stand start with left hand on a side-pull/undercling and right on a horizontal edge above head height. Two precision dead-points guard a the top out.  There is potential for a sit start, but it would be proper hard.

name: Palmer Roof Traverse
description: Kinda of obscure but once you are on it an awesome adventure! Trverse the lip of the roof with sidepulls, heel and toe hooks to a hold on the slab alowing passage to the top of the pinicale.

name: Platform Double Suede
description: Start as for Disco Lemonade, but instead of following the arête, climb straight up and into the slab.

name: Unnamed boulder
description: one of the best boulder we have found so far    a sit start on the right, tend left with your feet far underneath the roof, stop at ledges and move up.     a hold broke, but still climbable

name: Deep Water Boulder
description: Rock quality is not the best, but it isn’t bad. Start in the water and climb up pretty good holds to top out. Jump in and repeat.

name: HighTraverse
description: Start the same as The Traverse (V6), but ride the lip all the way over on good holds and top out.

name: Lower Boulder
description: SDS on good ledge. Move up on fun slopers and crimps. First move is big and up to the left using a cool round sloper/pinch. Top out. Good landing, but sometimes wet at base. Boulder on the left is off.

name: Traverse Boulder - Center Problem SDS
description: SDS with left hand on one pad crimp and right on 2-3 finger dished crimp. Crux is pulling up and off start holds. Cruise good holds to top and top out.

name: The Traverse
description: The test piece boulder problem for the Marquette area. It was done in the early 90's by Mike Moss at maybe V4, but a key hold had broken and it took another 4 years for Josh to piece it together. Start far right on your bum. With your hands on the lip of the overhang, drop below the lip and traverse 20 ft to your left till the overhang comes to an end and top out. Good luck.

name: Unknown
description: Upper body dependent problem with some heel hooking. Sit start on northwest side of boulder (lake on climbers left and parking lot on right side over hill) and traverse to left 6-7 moves then top out. Legs are under overhung boulder when not heel hooking.

name: Upper Boulder
description: There are a couple good lines (with some choss still) on this boulder. It is located above the traverse.

name: Waiting for the Morning Train
description: Sit start low on the left-center side to the right on the crack.

name: Warm Up Boulder
description: Sit Down Start on big incut jug. Move up through overhang on good holds.

name: The Fin
description: A nice traverse with a bad landing

name: The Pinacle
description: Three cruxes of 5.10 for a 80 foot pitch. sustained with one good rest at the bottom. the route follows the rappel line in the picture

name: Runes of the North
description: Start compressing the double arête feature with a left hand pinch and right hand sloper. Squeeze through the roof before devising some trickery to gain a distant edge. Hold it together for a few more moves and mantle over the lip of the boulder. Cryptic, tenuous, and powerful.

name: Crack
description: This is the most distinct line on the wall. Climb up on a solid flake to gain the hand crack.  Use face holds and crack to gain a ledge. Then continue up on easy 5th class to the top.  Large trees for TR or belay

name: Far Right Side
description: This route is on the far right of the wall.  Climb up the small right facing corner to gain a ledge.  Climb up and right under the roof. Undercling and lie back to gain the top.  To continue walk left and climb the wide flake to the tree

name: Variation on Crack
description: Climb the 5.7 hand crack until you each a horizontal break about 10-15 up.  Travers right about 8 feet until your under a small bulge, mantel up to access the small finger crack.  Climb to ledge.  Continue up though a small dihedral to the top.

name: 11.  Jack 2001
description: An excellent beginning leader route.  Begin at the crack to the right of the last climb.

name: 2.  March Madness
description: This is an excellent crack climb complete with liebacks and jams.  You'll nee a few bigger pieces to lead this one.

name: 3.  April Fools
description: This climb follows a series of ramps and medium cracks.

name: 4.  Hans Solo
description: This Route also require's some bigger cams.  Follow the jagged crack as it goes from an undercling to a big pull (crux move) to top out.

name: 5.  Toillette de la Porcupine
description: Start in the corner directly above the pile of porcupine crap.  Use the crack in the corner, then work over the right onto the face.  Bring small to medium nuts and cams.

name: 6.  Shin Dig
description: This is a great wandering climb over a scantily stting block.  Follow the crack along the right side of the block then pull up to mantle the block.  From here, follow the crack to the top.  Some micro cams to protect the thin crack at the top would be a good idea.

name: 7.  Wet Zipper
description: This is a great beginning leader route.  Climb the obvious corner/crack system.  Place gear in the crack at the top then stem (crux) to the top out.

name: Bad Nose Job
description: Begin with two hands matched on the lower of two crimps. Follow the protruding feature for an engaging few moves.

name: Birth Canal
description: Squeeze into Mother Nature's womb and reemerge a new being by achieving upward progress.

name: 1. Abe's Dirt Crack
description: Left most route at Suicide. Large flaring crack with decent protection. Watch for loose rock.

name: 2. Turbo Midget
description: This climb goes up a sustained overhanging wall to crux move on a pinch and small finger crack to pull the roof. Move to jugs to gain the anchors.

name: 3. El Matador
description: A zig zag route for sure.  Angle up and right till you get to the 2nd bolt then up and left then back right.  Holds right where you want them. Very continuous route.  Seeps between 2nd and 3rd bolts.

name: 4. Berke's Kitchen
description: Start just left of crag practice anchors.  Angle up and right making bigger moves off pretty good holds.  Crux at top, but holds where they need to be.

name: 5. Scrotum
description: This climb follows a nice thin slab to a crux dead point to a sloppy ledge with a jug on the far right (direct route and hardest). You may also follow the route left towards a piton and a awkward body jam to gain the fourth bolt.

name: 6. Stairway To Heaven
description: Follow a broken, zig-zag crack up as it widens to the anchors.  A smorgasbord of different techniques and movements on this one!

name: 7. Arbor Day
description: Stay out of the Stairway To Heaven crack!!!  Climb heavily featured face/slab, wandering slightly, through a sea of crisp edges and sidepulls.  Sometime's the top seeps.  Can be lead trad.

name: 8. 5th Grade Science Project
description: The defenite crux is just after clipping 3rd bolt. Work through a technical sequence on small crimps with almost no where to put feet. Watch out for loose rock in the first 10'.

name: 9. Evolution
description: Great warm up route. Left is easiest, right is hardest.

name: Bonestorm
description: Follow the Berke's Kitchen, but branch off to the left on the third bolt.

name: The Whirly Dirly
description: Couple options on start, mostly for additional options when the original start is too wet.  Straight variation is the most difficult.  Official route: step on on wet moss ledge, there are a couple high points to avoid too much moisture.  Move left and up and follow the nature flow of cracks.  Straight variation.  Start on the face to the left of the crack, once on continue up normal line.  Left Variation.  start far left on giant flake and right side of the first stair. Once off the ground tr4averse right to line and continue as normal.

name: Arrowhead
description: This route assend's the mid crag access rap stations.  Overgrown.  Not far climbers left of .....  slab start.

name: Bazinga!
description: Located on the west (left) side of the cliff band. The route tops out to climber's left of a large juniper bush right at the top of the cliff, where the terrain starts going steadily downward. Starts on a small shelf just left of a tree and ascends through a short sheer slab with shallow vertical grooves, into a crack system 10 feet left of an orange, left-facing dihedral. Crux is just right of a permanently wet spot halfway up. Scramble up vegetated ledges at the top to anchor on a tree. Fun route with good pro. Still some loose rock.

name: Book of Saturdays
description: This route is in the vein of adventure climbing the rock is dirty and some people might not think the rock to be to quality but I enjoyed the route. it stars on a long slab to a long 3rd class ledge were we belayed for a small part. you then climb through a chiminey to a corner that leads to a cave the rock here is sketch and is also the crux of the route. try and arange a belay in the cave then exit out onto the face and finish with a 100 foot pitch . walk off along ways either way.

name: Don't Take It For Granite.
description: Starts on a very distinct cleanish crisp 10' wide 60' long chunk of slab, optional belay over the top.  Continue on more slab into a wedge area where a right facing dihedral starts, belay here.  Climb dihedral for 30 and head up and left on face and ledge to a clump of junipers, belay.

name: East side rap route
description: Two anchors to start, higher middle of bald spot .  One ring anchor at the back of the major horizontal break, just after a 12' free air rappel.  One ring anchor when it really starts slabbing off till the next drop onto the final slab.  Watch for poison ivy at the bottom of this whole sector.  Two anchors will be place 2020 to make each station a set.

name: Route to Glory
description: Shares 2 pitches with "Book of Saturdays", but removes the first pitch and the long traverse.    Pitch 1- Starts on a large slab with thin cracks for protection, then traverses over to large grass filled crack.  Pulling grass can reveal the pro.  Large cams or large hexes are a must.  Wild country #6? .  Pitch 2- Belay stance is to the left of the major grassy chimney of the second pitch; Use small nuts to protect belay.  Look for stuck Omega Pacific nut to find out where to set up belay.  Follow the large chimney up to the roof.  Some protection can be found by venturing out onto the slab, but stay mostly to the chimney.  Crux can be found right before the cave area.  Pull a couple of exposed moves, and Metoliuschimney up a large overhanging crack. Traverse into the cave area.  Watch the loose rock, and maintain your footing.  Pitch 3-Belay from the cave area; protecting this can be tricky, but there should be a protectable crack out and around the corner of the cave.  Look for a stuck nut to give you and idea where to place.  Head out the cave and around the arete.  Easy pulls up to the top of the climb.  Top out and enjoy the view!

name: The Stritch Route
description: Start at the small rock pedestal/platform and climb  up between a tree and a bush, with athe tree on your right.  Angle up and left through a slab section with good feet to a groove and then skirt left around the small roof. You will find a small belay ledge at 45m on climbers left.  A #3 and #4 can be used at the belay. From the belay, go up some slightly vegetated slab to the top passing over a long ledge with some small bushes to sling, 30m. Belay from trees in the woods.

name: Swiss Army Crack
description: The route accends a long slab starting in a left facing corner for about 30 feet into a leftward horizontal traverse putting you at the base of a 100ft crack system. The crux comes right after the traverse. Well protected and loaded with holds this route has a little of everything!! There is a 4th class pitch if your starting from the bottom to get to the starting ledge. I would recomend rapping in and leading back out to avoid the loose scree at the base of the cliff.

name: Urushiol
description: An adventure route that starts in a crack on a steep slab and then does an airy traverse left to a large ledge with little for pro.  continue past the ledge up to a belay in the shrubs.  from this belay, find your way up to the top on vegetated slabs.

name: Walt's Crawlers
description: Either rap in from the top of the route which is exactly at the Overlook of the North country Trail or rap from the anchors at the north end of the Crag and walk to the bottom of the climb which is approximately 500 feet  south of the Book of Saturdays buttress.     The first pitch is 50m up slabs and corners to the base of a big block with a short vertical crack/chimney.    Second pitch goes up the crack and left across the brushy ledge finishing up a rotten corner and slab exit to the top.

name: When Snails Attack
description: Basically a 5th class gully.  At the pod head left up along a never ending shitty very chossy 4th class ramp/catwalk, solid pro is hard to find.  A direct line out the top of the pod is possible when dry, might redeem the route a bit, maybe?  Climbing above the pod is

name: Ball Dragon
description: SDS matched on a sloper rail. Weave under the tree with similar features to a funky crux before the top out. Dabby.

name: Ball Dragon Extension
description: Start with left hand in a four-finger pocket and right on a nearby edge. Trend left on sloping edges into the start of Ball Dragon.

name: Blue Suede
description: Start as for Marshmellow, but head left up the face with neat edges to a top out.

name: Fiery
description: SDS with right hand in the four-finger pocket and left on a side-pull. Trend right on the sloping lip before topping out in the dirty dihedral.

name: The Golden Fleece
description: SDS matched on a flake. Climb edges to what might be the best jug in all of Michigan. Top out.

name: Leather Chaps
description: Start as for Leather face, but head left through some slopers before topping out.

name: Leather Face
description: SDS matched on the prominent rail. Climb the face and top out.

name: Mouse Suicide
description: SDS with two crimps. Climb up and left through sloping rails and a few pockets, topping out as for Mouse Trap

name: Mouse Trap
description: SDS matched on a rail low on the left arête. Ride sweet edges on the epic refrigerator feature to the top out.

name: Plush
description: SDS on a sharp flake. Climb left through a few sloper rails before entering an exciting crux sequence with two sweet pockets. Top out. A quality, sustained line.

name: Red Velvet
description: Stand start matched on an undercling crimp rail. A few tenuous moves lead to an improbable lock-off crux guarding a mellow top out.

name: Big Mon Ting
description: Start as for Cosmic Brownie, but head left up the overhanging face on small, sharp edges. Hard crimping on a 35 degree overhang, classic. Detached blocks are off.

name: Cold Cut
description: Stand start with a left hand undercling and right in a pocket. Follow the line of pockets left and up the slab.

name: Cosmic Brownie
description: SDS with left hand on a low slot and right on the ledge around the right arête. A few moves of powerful compression lead to a crux dead-point just before the top out. Detached blocks are off.

name: Cribbage
description: Start as for short rib, but climb left through some sharp crimps before riding big ledges to the top out.

name: Fudge Round
description: SDS matched on an edge near the left arête. Climb up and left through side pulls to a powerful top out sequence. Detached blocks are off.

name: Oatmeal Creme Pie
description: Start as for Fudge Round, but climb right into the rib feature before surmounting the bulge and topping out.

name: The Outdoorsman
description: SDS with hands on the prominent shelves. Climb left on the sloping lip before topping out at the apex. Very flowy and surprisingly pumpy.

name: Ribeye
description: SDS on two triangular crimps. Climb over the bulge and left through the sweet rib features to a mellow top out.

name: Short Rib
description: SDS on your favorite edge of the incredible rib feature. A few powerful moves link into the top section of Ribeye.

name: Sim Simma
description: Same start holds as Ribeye (sandstone crimps). Traverse left through fun and interesting moves before topping out. Same exit as Fudge Rounds (V3-4).

name: Zebra Cakes
description: SDS on two small crimps. Some powerful slaps will take you into the middle of Swiss Rolls

name: Hope You Got Insurance And Shit
1.  That Shitty Mossy Crack
description: A shitty, mossy, dirty crack, that with some cleaning actually is fun. Balancing and flaring cracks make this a challenging trad climb.

name: 10.  Carpe Dildo
description: Begin on rightward-angling ramp and climb onto the huge ledge, then continue right to the left-facing dihedral. From there, meander up and left, using blocks and dihedrals. Top out left of cedar tree or use anchors for toprope. This route eats gear!

name: 11.  Between A Block And A Hard Place
description: Super classic!  There is a huge tree next to a nearly flat belay block at the base of this route. Start just right of first bolt and wander your way through the first three bolts to gain a series of large semi detached blocks. Bear hug, lieback, and tip-toe your way to a rest before the crux. After the crux section, a much more chill yet still on ya finish awaits.  Finish in vertical crack right of anchors.

name: 12.  Dripping With Cooties
description: Maybe the best line in the U.P.!  This one is on you right from the ground; recommended stick clipping the first bolt. Rest on a small ledge before tip-toeing your way up a sheer face.  Using your pocket microscope to look for foot holds, trust what little you can find. Technical, thin, and continuous.

name: 13.  More Cowbell
description: First route left of Rainbow Roof. Tough for first 20 feet; find underclings. Interesting climbing through varied terrain. A 60M rope with stretch just gets you down.

name: 14.  Indecent Exposure
description: * This route is accessed by climbing the Rainbow Catwalk.**  Start at the first set of anchors you encounter on the Catwalk.  A crux start (high left foot mantel type move to mondo jug rail) leads to blocky climbing, ending with a delicate small roof notch, followed by much chiller climbing to anchors.

name: 15.  God Bless Stretchy Pants
description: * This route is accessed by climbing the Rainbow Catwalk.**  Start at the second set of anchors on the Catwalk.  Crux at the start.  Gain a seam and scamper through lie-backs, ledges, and crimpers.  All decent holds.

name: 16.  Silver Sweetness
description: * This route is accessed by climbing the Rainbow Catwalk.**  Start at the third set of anchors on the Catwalk.  Third pitch of #16/17 (Silver Gold and Silver Sickness). Thin foot-dependent crux start to second bolt clipping jug.  Head up and right through blocks, to an awkward triangular dihedral.  Get your mantle on.  Zag left away from bolt line, farther than you think you should go, because that's where the feet are. Then cut back hard right and head up and right diagonally till it relents straight up.

name: 17.  Best Seat In The House
description: * This route is accessed by climbing the Rainbow Catwalk.**  Fourth and last set of anchors on the Catwalk. Crux start headed right and up gives way to a left-leaning series of interspersed finger- and hand-cracks. Heads up and right for last couple of bolts.  Wicked free air rappel from mid anchors, just left of hanging cedar tree on the lip of Rainbow Roof.

name: 18a.  Silver Gold
description: Leftmost route under Rainbow Roof. Climb ledges to face, anchors just under roof.  All 3 "Silver" routes (Gold, Sickness, and Sweetness) can be linked, but expect some rope drag.

name: 18b.  Silver Sickness
description: Extension of Silver Gold. From the chains, climb slightly right and strike out through the roof. Monkey your way through spread-out jugs to gain the arête and notch. A large ape index helps tremendously.

name: 19.  Revenge Of The Barking Spiders
description: Start on a large boulder at the base and pull out your mantle moves right away! Climb ledges to face, and one more mantle to reach the anchors in the roof.

name: 2.  High Gravity Day
description: Currently the leftmost bolted route. Starts just inside a hemlock corridor. A shorty but a goody with a stout, height dependent little roof.

name: 20.  1.21 Gigawatts
description: Climb 6 feet up to a rightward diagonal crack that leads up to the anchors of route #21.  Can be dirty?

name: 21.  Pepsi Showers
description: Very fun route. Climb a slab to an eye-catching pink/orange headwall right of an arete. Consistent fun climbing on interesting holds. Anchors in roof.

name: 22.  Crack Debit Or Credit
description: Marked by a crisp vertical section of crack near the first bolt. A low crux leads to smooth sailing all the way to the roof.

name: 23.  Welcome to the 906
description: From the main approach trail, this is the first climb you come to under the Rainbow Roof. A fun and safe introduction to Silver Mountain and an excellent first lead.

name: 24.  Sloth-Like Reflexes
description: Starts on a short right-facing arete. Crux off the deck, then a chill 5.8 through incut ledges and a couple of cool geode pockets. Pull out your mantle moves to reach the anchor!

name: 25a.  Golden Heart
description: Classic. Marked by the yellow, moss-covered, somewhat heart-shaped block at ¾ height.  Try not to get wedged into the alcoves...they feel safe to get into, but good luck getting out of them! Use the left set of anchors to top rope this pitch (to avoid a sharp edge).  Both Golden Heart/Bypass and Golden Heart/Direct can be linked, but watch for rope drag.

name: 25b.  Golden Heart Direct
description: Sickest route at Silver! This is the right bolt line from the top of Golden Heart. Belay from right set of anchors and incorporate a bolt about 5 feet to the right to get the belayer out of the fall zone. Head up and right to blank headwall. Huge moves between nothing holds. Get ready to log some flight time on this one. Does not let up until just below the anchors.

name: 25c.  Golden Heart Bypass
description: Left bolted line from the Golden Heart anchors.  Use the right set of anchors to belay.  Head up and left from anchors. Liebacks and crimps are the name of the game of this one.  Continuous.

name: 26a.  Anal Dwelling Butt Monkeys (ADBM)
description: Right-most climb under the Rainbow Roof.  Crux is getting to and from a large flake 10 feet up (consider stick-clipping).  Head up and right to beginning of orange and white streaked blocky overhanging terrain. Anchors are in a small roof; can be hard to spot from the ground.

name: 26b.  "ADBM" Extension, Left (Direct) Variation
description: *NOT YET BOLTED AS OF 12/2019**  Left variation of the second-pitch extension of Anal Dwelling Butt Monkeys. From first set of anchors, head up and left through multiple thin and strenuous overhangs to a second set of anchors. 65 feet, currently just anchors.  Soon to be equipped by P.P.

name: 26c  "ADBM" Extension, Right Variation
description: *NOT YET BOLTED AS OF 12/2019**  Right variation of the second-pitch extension of Anal Dwelling Butt Monkeys. From the anchors, bust out up and right into a left-facing dihedral and overhang. Monkey time! Traverse left out the lip of the overhang on surprisingly good jugs while working on your heel- and toe-hooking skills. Strenuous. Turn the lip and climb a short dihedral to second set of anchors on a ledge.  70 feet, anchors only. SOON TO BE EQUIPPED.

name: 26d.  "ADBM" Upper Pitch
description: Accessed by climbing first pitch of Beyond Hell/Above Heaven (#25) and traversing left after the first bolt of the second pitch. There is one bolt to protect the traverse and short downclimb to anchors on a small ledge.  From the anchors, step a bit left and climb up a short corner on thin holds to reach a major ledge. Continue up the dihedral system, utilizing the inside corner, arete, and right face. The dihedral switches abruptly from right facing to left facing at mid-route. Exit up and right. Tops out on a slab. While belaying, watch out for rope drag over sharp crystals at top.   65 feet, 10+ anchors.

name: 27.  Beyond Hell, Above Heaven
description: First route on the face right of the Rainbow Roof. Starts just right of a blunt arete. This one is a classic!  First pitch (5.10d): A 5.9 start gives way to gradually more difficult but super fun climbing, with a thought-provoking, but well-protected high crux. Hidden holds, right where you need them. 75 feet, 8 + anchors.  Second pitch (5.10c): Head left from first set of anchors into a crack system. Climb slabby crack to large blocks, then up onto a sizeable ledge under a roof. Move left to exit the roof, straddling precariously on a sharp arete, then trend rightward up a slab to anchors below a large oak tree. Easy to top out and walk off.  70 feet, 7 + anchors.    Both pitches can be linked, but be prepared for a little rope drag at the end. TWO RAPPELS ARE NECESSARY - KNOT THE ENDS OF YOUR ROPES!.  If there's a lot of traffic on the route its polite to rap from the top anchors down to the extension pitch anchors(second set) of Butt Monkeys, its actualy a better repel option to begin with in my opinion.  The anchors are 25' climbers left of Beyond Hell, Above Heaven's first pitch anchors.

name: 28a.  Intergalactic STDs
description: First pitch, Traverse Variation (5.10b): Starts immediately right of Beyond Hell/Above Heaven (#25) and traverses right, following a nearly horizontal hand crack for first 10 feet. Then climb up and continue traversing right using the same crack for your feet. After the fourth bolt, follow the bolts up and diagonally right to anchors on a small ledge. 60 feet, 6 + anchors.

name: 28b.  Intergalatic STDs
description: First pitch, Direct Variation (5.11b): Starts just left of an obvious diagonal crack system. Climb a sheer face on thin crimps and sidepulls to the same set of anchors as the Traverse Variation. Sustained climbing. 50 feet, 5 + anchors.

name: 28c.  Intergalatic STDs
description: Second pitch (5.10d): Wander up and right through surprisingly clean jugs to a ledge next to a large pine tree, then trend left up a beautiful black face to some bulges. Stay right of the bolt line for last 2 bolts, then traverse left to second set of anchors. 70 feet, 8 + anchors.    Can be linked into one pitch from both variations (with some rope drag). TWO RAPPELS NECESSARY.  KNOT YOUR ENDS!

name: 29.  Alpha Nerd
description: Starts between the alternate first pitch variations for Intergalatic STDs (#26). Extremely varied terrain. Unfortunately the start of this one is not consistant with the rest of the route (harder). Climb tenuous moves up a thin face past 3 bolts.  Crux is clipping the second bolt; recommended to stick clip the second bolt if at all possible.   After the crux, climb through a relaxed slab section to a finger crack a mid route. Crux a bit through the crack and head up and left, just circumventing a small roof section.  Then head back right and climb a heavily featured blocky section to gain a rightward leaning crack system to the anchors.   100 feet, 10 bolts + anchors.

name: 3.  Ten Meters of Teamwork
description: An easy slab leads to an awkward dihedral. Huff and grunt to surmount a small roof, then find some hidden holds to unlock the short headwall to the anchors.

name: 30.  Sexus (aka The Diagonal Crack)
description: Climb the obvious diagonal crack for 40 feet, then head up a short, blocky face to a big pine tree on a ledge.  Trad + chains on pine tree.

name: 31.  Footloose (aka The Sport Route)
description: The lower trail from the climber cul-de-sac puts you near at the bottom of this route. This was the first bolted route at Silver in the early 1990s. Start right of the diagonal crack system. A spicy, technical route with several cruxy sections. Sustained but rewarding.  80 feet, 9 bolts + anchors.

name: 32a.  Queen Bee
description: Ascend a heavily featured face to a crack, then continue up and right through a chill slab. The first set of anchors are just above a nice ledge. (60 feet, 6 bolts + anchors).   The extension ups the grade to 5.11b. Battle through an awkward diagonal crack to better holds on a headwall. Anchors below a small roof. (20 feet, 2 bolts + anchors).

name: 32b.  Queen Bee Extension
description: This is the full Queen Bee route. Ascend a heavily featured face to a crack, then continue up and right through a chill slab to a nice ledge. Clip one of the bolts of the anchor and battle through an awkward diagonal crack to better holds on a headwall. Anchors below a small roof.

name: 33.  Swamp Thing
description: Only for desperate and deprived tradsters.  Usually wet and dirty.  Climb the obvious left-leaning, greenish crack 10 feet right of Queen Bee (#30). Use Queen Bee's anchors.

name: 34.  Love Street
description: Very cool waves in the rock at the start are evidence of glacial scarring from the last ice age, approximately 10,000 years ago. This is a thin and tight route with a sick crux about 15 feet below the anchors. Climb past the anchors for Hooters (AKA Resurrection, #33), up and left to this route's anchors.  70 feet, 8 bolts + anchors.

name: 36.  Matrix (aka Buck Angel Crack)
description: This route starts directly below the short section of fist crack 8' off the ground and 10' right of the bolts on Resurrection. Climb through the fist crack to a mantel of sorts, which gains you access to great gear in the finger crack above. Bust a move left through a compression sequence followed by a devious crux that is equal parts power and balance. Once through the crux you will be rewarded with good gear and eventually a no hands rest. The rest of the route is more moderate, around 10+ but requires a full arsenal of techniques and stays with you.  100 feet, trad + anchors.

name: 37. Don't Panic, and Bring Your Towel
description: One of the best cracks in the UP, thoughtful movement with creative jamming and an easily protected crux.Start in a crack that points up and left to a 6" crack. Follow the line of weakness above the OW to a finger crack. Delicate movement at the top to gain the slopey ledge. Traverse right on the ledge to the next crack system. Proceed up this next line of weakness up to a small ledge below a triangular cutout with a two inch crack around halfway. From here, follow the left line of weakness up through the cutout into a stellar left facing finger crack. Take the finger crack up and follow the blocks to the anchors.You can take a right at the upper triangular cutout through the shrub, but the climbing is better (and harder) if you choose the left crack system.This route was originally named "Lucky Scars" by P.P. and L.P. when established as a top rope climb. It likely joins the end of wine line at the slopey ledge. It does have the potential to extend into the blank upper face with some more cleaning, an anchor, and a couple bolts to make a gnarly mixed route following the first line of weakness strait up, past the slopey ledge and into the blank headwall.

name: 38.  Wine Line
description: The farthest route climbers right on the main wall, just before you enter the *** POISON IVY*** patch.  Start in front of the tree that's branches touch the wall.  The Line begins with a short finger crack climbing off a small ledge at one meter.  Climb up the seams, and out from under the tree to the sunshine above.  Continue up the broken cracks up and right to a tree anchor high above.

name: 39.  Ivy's Poison
description: Start at the base of a ledge system which leads to a face split by a crack system.  Climbs just right of white, orange, and black streaked section.

name: 4.  Yo Momma
description: Start from a small ledge under the right side of Desolation Roof. Begin climbing up and right, following a diagonal crack. Step over a notch and make your way to a rightward-leaning slab. Finish left at top of slab. Shares last bolt and anchors with #5. Clip the perma draw on the third bolt to clean as you descend.

name: 40.  Big Laughing Gym
description: Different style than most of Silver Mountain.  Step up onto the second ledge and hope you warmed up well enough. Boulder through the bottom with excellent gear into the top of the crack, aaaaaand it's over.  Anchors do not have rings and are pretty far back from the top of the crack, if looking to TR bring long cord or webbing.  Would be an excellent highball if the landing zone was better.  As the first ascensionist is unknown, the name is a suggestion.  35 feet, trad + anchors.

name: 5. Yo Momma's Crack
description: Start on Yo Momma.  Once you gain the ledge, trend up and right using the obvious crack system to the left of the slab.  Takes gear well.  Caution: slippery when wet.  Finish on Yo Momma's anchors.

name: 6.  Yo Sister
description: Technical and thuggy crux off the deck; stick clip first bolt. Unlock the wicked roof, then trend up and right on consistant crimps staying on the face right of the arête, don't reach around the arete till your under the last bolt on the slab.  Shares last bolt and anchors with #4.

name: 7.  Super Mario's Magic Mushroom
description: Climb slab to a roof 30 feet up with a splitter crack in it. Pull the heinous roof crux, and trust those feet to surmount and clip the next bolt.  Finish on vert/slab.

name: 8.  Geriatric Death Metal
description: A little bit of everything on this one! Slab to a large ledge at 15 feet. Grapple with an interesting Texas-shaped block, move left onto wavy overhangs and a thin headwall, then pull onto a good ledge, then a slab finish.

name: 9.  Rainbow Catwalk
description: It’s getting crazy up here in the 906! This route traverses left to right through routes #7-12, clipping a bolt each on routes 7, 10, 11, and 12 along with a few in between. Usually climbed to access the start of the routes above the Rainbow Roof, but is a fun route in and of itself. Also good for experiencing a free-air rappel over the roof.   Start left of route #7 and head right, aiming for a horizontal ledge system over the Rainbow Roof. 70-130 feet, 6-13b's + anchors.    ***Communicate with fellow climbers as to your plans to do this route and the routes it accesses, because it crosses existing routes and climbs above routes below the roof!  If it's a busy day at the crag, do not attempt!!***

name: [Redacted]
description: *MIXED CLIMB**   Resurrection-To bring back to life-I spotted this line in the fall of 2014 and came back to clean and work it summer 2015. Upon setting up a line from the trees above, I discovered two anchor bolts at mid-cliff height slightly left and above the line(later learned are the anchor bolts for the route Love Street, which has been chopped and waiting to be rebolted). I began to clean the lichen and moss from the crack system as best as possible, burning up a wire brush in the process. Lower down on the route, I uncovered two chopped bolts in thick lichen, protecting the opening moves off the ground.  The route has been re-bolted to its original state.  Tight start on side-pulls past 3 bolts leading to a left-leaning finger/hand crack.  After crack peters out, head up and right past 2 more bolts to first set of anchors.  Standard rack up to #1, 5 bolts, + anchors.

name: Mosquito Bait
description: Based on the amount of lichen and moss I scrubbed off this thing I'm guessing no one has climbed it. Please let me know if I am wrong about this. Start left hand low on arete, right on an undercling grip around right arête, and a right heel. Slap your way to the top. There exists a low start the would be proper burly.

name: Sneaking Past the Guard
description: Go right just before the first set of stairs. Stay low, after about 100 yards you'll see it on the left with a small tree (5 inch in diameter) about a foot and a half away from the cliff. BETA SPRAY ALERT: Sit start matched on a right slanting rail and a left foot backstep. Left hand up to a jug, throw a right heel up, make a bump to an undercling, switch to a toe, then fling yourself up to a left hand slightly sloping rail while making sure you sneak past the guard of the small tree behind you. Finish out left. It would be better if the tree wasn't there but I didn't want to tick anyone off by cutting it down. All in all its a pretty dang good Boulder problem.

name: Finger Crack
description: The name says it all

name: Moss Jugs
description: Just to the left of the finger crack taking good holds to a hand jam

name: Roof Traverse
description: This climb is around the overlook area and starts to the right under the roof.

name: Shrinking flat crack
description: This boulder is just below the biggest falls around the corner. There is a good flat platform where you can stand to start the route. Higher water would prevent access... Start where the crack is the widest and try to get to a pretty good ledge past the narrower second higher horizontal crack. Feet are good and bad.  This route seems to be cleaner than others in the area.  Ie leas Moss falling in your eyes.
